2g00m0fe019000c.html \"Evangelion Special: Genesis of a major manga\"]\u2014''Mainichi Daily News''\n* [https://www.webcitation.org/5PSTPs1dF?url=http://mdn.mainichi-msn.co.jp/features/archive/news/2006/05/20060506p2g00m0fe031000c.html \"Evangelion Special: For producer Otsuki, success not always a bed of roses\"]\u2014''Mainichi Daily News''\n* [http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/feature/2002-06-11 \"Understanding Evangelion\"]\u2014Anime News Network\n\n== External links ==\n{{Portal|1990s}}\n{{Wikiquote|Neon Genesis Evangelion}}\n\n;Official websites\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20010402055013/http://www.gainax.co.jp/ ''Neon Genesis Evangelion'']\u2014Gainax official ''Evangelion'' page {{in lang|ja}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051218092346/http://www.madman.com.au/nge/ Madman Entertainment ''Evangelion'' page]\n* [http://www.evangelion.co.jp/ \u65b0\u4e16\u7d00\u30a8\u30f4\u30a1\u30f3\u30b2\u30ea\u30aa\u30f3]\u2014King Records ''Evangelion'' page {{in lang|ja}}\n\n;Articles and information\n* {{IMDb title|0112159|Neon Genesis Evangelion}}\n* {{Ann|anime|49|Neon Genesis Evangelion}}\n* {{Curlie|Arts/Animation/Anime/Titles/N/Neon_Genesis_Evangelion/|''Neon Genesis Evangelion''}}\n\n{{Navboxes|list=\n{{Neon Genesis Evangelion}}\n{{Hideaki Anno}}\n{{Anime Grand Prix}}\n{{Animation Kobe TV Feature Award}}\n{{Gainax}}\n{{Tatsunoko Production}}\n{{Toonami-anime}}\n}}\n\n[[Category:Neon Genesis Evangelion| ]]\n[[Category:1995 anime television series]]\n[[Category:1996 Japanese television series endings]]\n[[Category:ADV Films]]\n[[Category:Animated science fiction television series]]\n[[Category:Anime composed by Shir\u014d Sagisu]]\n[[Category:Anime with original screenplays]]\n[[Category:Apocalyptic anime and manga]]\n[[Category:Coming-of-age anime and manga]]\n[[Category:Existentialist works]]\n[[Category:Fiction set in 2015]]\n[[Category:Gainax]]\n[[Category:Japan Self-Defense Forces in fiction]]\n[[Category:Madman Entertainment anime]]\n[[Category:Mecha anime and manga]]\n[[Category:Metafictional television series]]\n[[Category:Mythology in popular culture]]\n[[Category:Philosophical anime and manga]]\n[[Category:Post-apocalyptic animated television series]]\n[[Category:Psychological anime and manga]]\n[[Category:Science fiction anime and manga]]\n[[Category:Tatsunoko Production]]\n[[Category:Television series about ancient astronauts]]\n[[Category:Television series set in 2015]]\n[[Category:Television series set in the 2010s]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Tokyo]]\n[[Category:Toonami]]\n[[Category:TV Tokyo shows]]\n[[Category:Works about depression]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about dysfunctional families]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about robots]]\n", "name_user": "Xfansd", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eInfluence and legacy", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neon_Genesis_Evangelion"}
{"title_page": "Vic Coppersmith-Heaven", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Vic Coppersmith-Heaven\n| image               = \n| caption             = \n| image_size          = \n| background          = non_performing_personnel\n| birth_name          = Victor Smith \n| birth_place         = [[England]]\n| birth_date          = {{birth year and age|1945|08}}\n| instrument          = \n| genre               = \n| occupation          = [[Audio engineering|Sound engineer]], [[record producer]]\n| years_active        = 1961\u2013present\n| label               = \n| associated_acts     = [[The Jam]], [[Black Sabbath]], [[The Rolling Stones]], [[Joe Cocker]], various\n| website             = \n}}\n\n'''Vic Coppersmith-Heaven''' (born '''Victor Smith''', August 1945, England)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://companycheck.co.uk/director/903556542/MR-VICTOR-COPPERSMITH-HEAVEN/summary|title=MR VICTOR COPPERSMITH-HEAVEN director information|website=Company Check|accessdate=17 September 2018}}</ref> is an English [[audio engineering|sound engineer]] and record producer, best known for his production work with [[The Jam]].\n\n==Career==\nSmith worked in the recording studios at [[Polydor Records|Polydor]] after leaving school in 1961. By 1967 he worked as the engineer on [[Cat Stevens]]' album ''[[Matthew and Son (album)|Matthew and Son]]'', and on [[The Rolling Stones]]', ''[[Let It Bleed]]''. Smith then engineered other hits such as \"[[Honky Tonk Women]]\" and [[Joe Cocker]]'s \"[[With a Little Help from My Friends]]\".<ref name=\"About The Young Idea\">{{cite book\n| first= Mike \n| last= Nicholls\n| year= 1984\n| title= About The Young Idea: The Story of The Jam 1972 \u2013 1982\n| edition= 1st\n| publisher= Proteus Books Ltd \n| location= London\n| page= 24\n| isbn= 0-86276-176-X}}</ref>  In early 1968 he produced [[the Nashville Teens]]' recording of \"[[All Along the Watchtower]]\", the earliest [[cover version]] of [[Bob Dylan]]'s song, which was released as a single in the UK and Europe on [[Decca Records]] some six months before [[Jimi Hendrix]]'s hit version.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nashville-teens.com/Main06.htm |title=Their Music |publisher=The Nashville Teens |date= |accessdate=2015-10-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://expo67-cavestones.blogspot.co.uk/2012/08/the-nashville-teens-sun-dog.html |title=Opulent Conceptions: The Nashville Teens - Sun-Dog |publisher=Expo67-cavestones.blogspot.co.uk |date=2012-08-21 |accessdate=2015-10-10}}</ref>\n\nHe produced a number of artists, including [[Sunforest (band)|Sunforest]], who released an album on Nova, [[Deram Records]]'s short-lived [[progressive rock|prog rock]] record label, in 1969. Sunforest was a [[psychedelic rock|psych]]-[[folk music|folk]] all-female British-American [[trio (music)|trio]]. Two of their recordings, \"Overture to the Sun\" and \"Lighthouse Keeper\", later emerged in a re-recorded form on the soundtrack to [[Stanley Kubrick]]'s film, ''[[A Clockwork Orange (film)|A Clockwork Orange]]''. Smith also produced [[Tinkerbells Fairydust]], as well as [[Peter Sarstedt]]'s third [[United Artists Records|United Artists]] album, ''Every Word You Say (Is Written Down)'', in 1971.\n\nWith Smith at the helm, [[Gravy Train (rock group)|Gravy Train]] [[sound recording and reproduction|recorded]] their fourth album, ''Staircase to the Day''. [[Dawn Records]] released it in 1974.<ref>[http://www.davalmusic.co.uk/gravytrain.htm]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090325101012/http://www.davalmusic.co.uk/gravytrain.htm |date=25 March 2009 }}</ref>\n\nIn the mid 1970s Smith worked at Polydor's old studios in [[Stratford Place]], London, and was pleased to get involved with The Jam's recordings. \"I remember that first [[concert|gig]] [[Chris Parry (producer)|Chris Parry]] took me to\" said Smith. \"It was a period of real excitement and although there were only between 15 and 20 people there, it was a great show with amazing spirit and energy\".<ref name=\"About The Young Idea\"/> Later when The Jam slimmed their team of two producers down to one, the then-renamed Coppersmith-Heaven had developed the group's sound with harmonised guitars and acoustic textures. The Jam released their third LP, ''[[All Mod Cons]]'' in November 1978.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://maniacmusic.blog.hr/2008/09/1625415988/the-jam-the-sound-of-the-jam-188mb.html |title=The Jam \u2013 The Sound of the Jam |publisher=Maniac Music |date=29 April 1977 |accessdate=2013-12-03}}</ref>\n\n[[The Vapors]] track, \"[[Turning Japanese]]\", was produced by Coppersmith-Heaven and reached the top three in the [[UK Singles Chart]], at the same time that The Jam's \"[[Going Underground]]\" was at [[hit record|number one]].<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\">{{cite book\n| first= David\n| last= Roberts\n| year= 2006\n| title= British Hit Singles & Albums\n| edition= 19th\n| publisher= Guinness World Records Limited \n| location= London\n| page= 582\n| isbn= 1-904994-10-5}}</ref> In September 1980, when \"[[Start!]]\" reached [[List of number-one singles from the 1980s (UK)|number one]] it was Coppersmith-Heaven's second production credit on a chart topping [[hit single]].<ref name=\"500 Number One Hits\">{{cite book\n| first= Jo\n| last= Rice\n| year= 1982\n| title= The Guinness Book of 500 Number One Hits\n| edition= 1st\n| publisher= Guinness Superlatives Ltd \n| location= Enfield, Middlesex\n| page= 207\n| isbn= 0-85112-250-7}}</ref> By the end of 1980 Coppersmith-Heaven's term with The Jam ended. \"[[Funeral Pyre]]\" was their first single to be produced by Pete Wilson instead of Coppersmith-Heaven, and was also unique in giving the writing credits to the band.\n\nIn 1987, he was responsible, with producer [[Nick Glennie-Smith]] and singer [[Kenny Young]], for the album ''Transmissions''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/artist/Gentlemen+Without+Weapons |title=Gentlemen Without Weapons Discography |publisher=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=2013-12-03}}</ref> under the group name Gentlemen Without Weapons.  Young had been concerned about environmental issues for years and in 1989 he co-founded the [[rainforest]] conservation organization, Earth Love Fund, with the same colleagues. The same year, Coppersmith-Heaven worked with [[Black Sabbath]] for the second time, producing their album ''[[The Eternal Idol]]''. A year later, he produced a single for the Kent-based [[indie music|indie]] band, [[The Claim (band)|The Claim]], entitled \"Wait And See\", at the ex-Jam drummer [[Rick Buckler]]'s studio.\n\n[[Irritant (band)|Irritant]]'s 2007 single \"Voice of the Siren\", described by the [[BBC]] as a \"gargantuan rock classic\", was produced by Coppersmith-Heaven. In 2008, Coppersmith-Heaven produced four tracks for The Q's debut [[Gramophone record|EP]] ''Issues'', which was released as a limited edition vinyl on Time For Action Records on 20 November.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://myspace.com/theqhq |title=The Q &#124; Listen and Stream Free Music, Albums, New Releases, Photos, Videos |publisher=Myspace.com |date= |accessdate=2013-12-03}}</ref>\n\n==Credits==\n*''[[Matthew and Son (album)|Matthew and Son]]'' \u2013 [[Cat Stevens]] (1967)\n*''[[Skip Bifferty (album)|Skip Bifferty]]'' \u2013 [[Skip Bifferty]] (1968)\n*''Soul of a Man''- Robbi Curtice (1968)\n*''Tinkerbells Fairydust'' \u2013 [[Tinkerbells Fairydust]] (1969)\n*''Heavy Blues'' \u2013 [[Champion Jack Dupree]] (1969)\n*''[[Sound of Sunforest]]'' \u2013 [[Sunforest (band)|Sunforest]] (1969)\n*''Peter Wyngarde'' \u2013 [[Peter Wyngarde]] (1970)\n*''Every Word You Say (Is Written Down)'' \u2013 [[Peter Sarstedt]] (1971)\n*''[[Black Sabbath Vol. 4]]'' \u2013 [[Black Sabbath]] (1972)\n*''Rock 'n Roll Gypsies'' \u2013 [[Vinegar Joe (band)|Vinegar Joe]] (1972)\n*''[[Bodacious DF]]'' - Bodacious DF (1973)\n*''[[Snafu (Snafu album)|SNAFU]]'' \u2013 [[Snafu (band)|Snafu]] (1973)\n*''[[Rocka Rolla]]'' \u2013 [[Judas Priest]] (1974)\n*''[[In the City (The Jam album)|In the City]]'' \u2013 [[The Jam]] (1977)\n*''[[This Is the Modern World]]'' \u2013 The Jam (1977)\n*''[[All Mod Cons]]'' \u2013 The Jam (1978)\n*''[[The Jolt]]'' \u2013 The Jolt (1978)\n*''[[Setting Sons]]'' \u2013 The Jam (1979)\n*''Hour Glass'' \u2013 [[Johnny Warman]] (1979)\n*''[[Sound Affects]]'' \u2013 The Jam (1980)\n*''[[New Clear Days]]'' - [[The Vapors]] (1980)\n*''[[Playing in the City]]'' \u2013 [[Barratt Band]] (1981)\n*''[[Vocabulary (album)|Vocabulary]]'' \u2013 [[The Europeans (band)|The Europeans]] (1983)\n*''Step Off The Edge'' \u2013 [[The Venetians (Australian band)|The Venetians]] (1985)\n*''[[The Eternal Idol]]'' \u2013 Black Sabbath (1987)\n*''Transmissions'' \u2013 Gentlemen Without Weapons (1987)\n*''Island of Ghosts'' \u2013 Rossy (1991)\n*''The Rainforest Album'' - Earthrise (1992)\n*''The Gate'' \u2013 Joji Hirota (1998)\n*''Issues'' \u2013 The Q (2008)<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/vic-coppersmith-heaven-mn0000208257 |title=Vic Coppersmith-Heaven &#124; Credits |publisher=AllMusic |date= |accessdate=2013-12-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/vic-smith-mn0000174119 |title=Vic Smith &#124; Credits |publisher=AllMusic |date=12 May 1975 |accessdate=2013-12-03}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{The Jam}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Coppersmith-Heaven, Vic}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British audio engineers]]\n[[Category:English record producers]]\n[[Category:20th-century British engineers]]\n[[Category:21st-century British engineers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Vic Coppersmith-Heaven\n| image               = \n| caption             = \n| image_size          = \n| background          = non_performing_personnel\n| birth_name          = Victor Smith \n| birth_place         = [[England]]\n| birth_date          = {{birth year and age|1945|08}}\n| instrument          = \n| genre               = \n| occupation          = [[Audio engineering|Sound engineer]], [[record producer]]\n| years_active        = 1961\u2013present\n| label               = \n| associated_acts     = [[The Jam]], [[Black Sabbath]], [[The Rolling Stones]], [[Joe Cocker]], various\n| website             = \n}}\n\n'''Vic Coppersmith-Heaven''' (born '''Victor Smith''', August 1945, England)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://companycheck.co.uk/director/903556542/MR-VICTOR-COPPERSMITH-HEAVEN/summary|title=MR VICTOR COPPERSMITH-HEAVEN director information|website=Company Check|accessdate=17 September 2018}}</ref> is an English [[audio engineering|sound engineer]] and record producer, best known for his production work with [[The Jam]].\n\n==Career==\nSmith worked in the recording studios at [[Polydor Records|Polydor]] after leaving school in 1961. By 1967 he worked as the engineer on [[Cat Stevens]]' album ''[[Matthew and Son (album)|Matthew and Son]]'', and on [[The Rolling Stones]]', ''[[Let It Bleed]]''. Smith then engineered other hits such as \"[[Honky Tonk Women]]\" and [[Joe Cocker]]'s \"[[With a Little Help from My Friends]]\".<ref name=\"About The Young Idea\">{{cite book\n| first= Mike \n| last= Nicholls\n| year= 1984\n| title= About The Young Idea: The Story of The Jam 1972 \u2013 1982\n| edition= 1st\n| publisher= Proteus Books Ltd \n| location= London\n| page= 24\n| isbn= 0-86276-176-X}}</ref>  In early 1968 he produced [[the Nashville Teens]]' recording of \"[[All Along the Watchtower]]\", the earliest [[cover version]] of [[Bob Dylan]]'s song, which was released as a single in the UK and Europe on [[Decca Records]] some six months before [[Jimi Hendrix]]'s hit version.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nashville-teens.com/Main06.htm |title=Their Music |publisher=The Nashville Teens |date= |accessdate=2015-10-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://expo67-cavestones.blogspot.co.uk/2012/08/the-nashville-teens-sun-dog.html |title=Opulent Conceptions: The Nashville Teens - Sun-Dog |publisher=Expo67-cavestones.blogspot.co.uk |date=2012-08-21 |accessdate=2015-10-10}}</ref>\n\nHe produced a number of artists, including [[Sunforest (band)|Sunforest]], who released an album on Nova, [[Deram Records]]'s short-lived [[progressive rock|prog rock]] record label, in 1969. Sunforest was a [[psychedelic rock|psych]]-[[folk music|folk]] all-female British-American [[trio (music)|trio]]. Two of their recordings, \"Overture to the Sun\" and \"Lighthouse Keeper\", later emerged in a re-recorded form on the soundtrack to [[Stanley Kubrick]]'s film, ''[[A Clockwork Orange (film)|A Clockwork Orange]]''. Smith also produced [[Tinkerbells Fairydust]], as well as [[Peter Sarstedt]]'s third [[United Artists Records|United Artists]] album, ''Every Word You Say (Is Written Down)'', in 1971.\n\nWith Smith at the helm, [[Gravy Train (rock group)|Gravy Train]] [[sound recording and reproduction|recorded]] their fourth album, ''Staircase to the Day''. [[Dawn Records]] released it in 1974.<ref>[http://www.davalmusic.co.uk/gravytrain.htm]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090325101012/http://www.davalmusic.co.uk/gravytrain.htm |date=25 March 2009 }}</ref>\n\nIn the mid 1970s Smith worked at Polydor's old studios in [[Stratford Place]], London, and was pleased to get involved with The Jam's recordings. \"I remember that first [[concert|gig]] Chris Parry took me to\" said Smith. \"It was a period of real excitement and although there were only between 15 and 20 people there, it was a great show with amazing spirit and energy\".<ref name=\"About The Young Idea\"/> Later when The Jam slimmed their team of two producers down to one, the then-renamed Coppersmith-Heaven had developed the group's sound with harmonised guitars and acoustic textures. The Jam released their third LP, ''[[All Mod Cons]]'' in November 1978.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://maniacmusic.blog.hr/2008/09/