g treated as a noble, and maintaining her paper-making studio, are considered, as well as her access to the temple's library. On the way home, Myne hears about a strange man looking for her and is told to be cautious. That night, Gunther meets with Otto to discuss their future, only for Otto to reveal he's been offered a position by Benno to help support his newborn child. The next day, Benno reveals that someone broke into the Merchant Guild, and the suspect is most likely a spy from the temple who's looking for Myne. He also finds out that Freida bought Myne's recipe for cooking with sugar, much to his chagrin due to a lack of supplies and accessibility, but plans to make her a future offer. At the temple, Ferdinand reports his spy's findings to the High Bishop, promoting her potential high value, but the High Bishop counters with plans to abuse Myne for her mana. The day of Myne's inauguration arrives, but as she walks the halls of the temple, she hears derogatory commoner remarks aimed in her direction. She meets with Ferdinand, recites the prayer to be an apprentice, and is handed her blue robes, the sign of clergy coming from a noble family. She then meets her three attendants, called \"retainers\". She meets a quiet young man named Fran, a conceited young girl named Delia, and a pompous young boy named Gil, all who wear gray-robed uniforms, indicating the lowest level member of the temple. When Ferdinand is called away, it is determined that, while Gil is brash and Fran is devoted to the temple, Delia out secretly out to get Myne, per the High Boshop's orders.\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber       = 16\n| Title               = Blue Robes and Uncommon Sense\n| TranslitTitle       = Aoi I to Kotonaru J\u014dshiki\n| NativeTitle         = \u9752\u3044\u8863\u3068\u7570\u306a\u308b\u5e38\u8b58\n| NativeTitleLangCode = ja\n| OriginalAirDate     = {{Start date|2020|4|11}}\n| ShortSummary        = \n}}<!--\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber       = 17\n| Title               = \n| TranslitTitle       = Ataerubeki Mono\n| NativeTitle         = \u4e0e\u3048\u308b\u3079\u304d\u3082\u306e\n| NativeTitleLangCode = ja\n| OriginalAirDate     = {{Start date|2020|4|18}}\n| ShortSummary        = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber       = \n| Title               = \n| TranslitTitle       = \n| NativeTitle         = \n| NativeTitleLangCode = ja\n| OriginalAirDate     = {{Start date|2020|4|}}\n| ShortSummary        = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber       = \n| Title               = \n| TranslitTitle       = \n| NativeTitle         = \n| NativeTitleLangCode = ja\n| OriginalAirDate     = {{Start date|2020|4|}}\n| ShortSummary        = \n}}-->\n}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of anime episodes|Ascendance of a Bookworm]]\n", "name_user": "Toramaru", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePart 2 (2020)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Ascendance_of_a_Bookworm_episodes"}
{"title_page": "Murder of Dora Bloch", "text_new": "{{short description|Hostage murdered after Operation Entebbe}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates| date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Dora Bloch\n| image         = Flickr - Government Press Office (GPO) - Dora Bloch's Family Pays Last Respects.jpg\n| alt           =\n| caption       = Family members at the grave of Dora Bloch\n| birth_name    = Dora Feinberg\n| birth_date    = 1901/2\n| birth_place   = [[Jaffa]], [[Ottoman Empire]]\n| death_date    = 1976 (aged 74/75)\n| death_place   = [[Kampala]], Uganda\n| burial_place  = [[Har HaMenuchot]]\n| nationality   = British-Israeli\n| other_names   = Devorah Bloch\n| spouse        = Aharon Bloch\n| children      = 3\n| occupation    =\n| years_active  =\n| known_for     = Killed on order of [[Idi Amin]] after [[Operation Entebbe]]\n}}\n\nIn June 1976, '''Dora Bloch''' ({{Lang-he|\u05d3\u05d5\u05e8\u05d4 \u05d1\u05dc\u05d5\u05da}}), a dual Israeli-British citizen, was a hostage on Air France Flight 139 from [[Tel Aviv]] to Paris, which was hijacked after a stopover in [[Athens]] and rerouted to [[Entebbe]], Uganda. Bloch became ill on the plane and was taken to a hospital in [[Kampala]]; she was not rescued with the other hostages during [[Operation Entebbe]], but went missing from the hospital. Her disappearance led to Britain cutting diplomatic ties with Uganda. Her body was discovered in 1979 in a sugar plantation near the capital. In February 2007, declassified British documents confirmed that she was killed on the order of [[Idi Amin]].\n\n==Biography==\nDora Feinberg was born in [[Jaffa]], then a part of the [[Mutasarrifate of Jerusalem]], [[Ottoman Empire]] and now a part of Israel.<ref name=ap/><ref name=SHT/> Her father, Joseph Feinberg, was among the founders of the Jewish agricultural settlement of [[Rishon LeZion]].<ref name=ap/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rishonlezion.muni.il/eng/Pages/HistoryofRishonLeZion.aspx|title=History of Rishon LeZion|publisher=[[Rishon LeZion]] Municipality|accessdate=5 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170320162853/http://www.rishonlezion.muni.il/eng/pages/historyofrishonlezion.aspx|archive-date=20 March 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> After her father's death, she was raised by an uncle in Egypt. She moved to Jerusalem as an adult.<ref name=David/> She spoke Hebrew, Arabic, Russian, German, Italian, and English.<ref name=ap>{{cite news |url=http://archives.chicagotribune.com/1976/07/15/page/2/article/hostage-auntie-bloch-loved-kids|title=Hostage 'Auntie' Bloch Loved Kids|author=Associated Press|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=15 July 1976|accessdate=5 March 2017|page=2}}</ref> In 1920, she met Aharon Bloch ({{Lang-he|\u05d0\u05d4\u05e8\u05d5\u05df \u05d0\u05d4\u05e8\u05df \u05d1\u05dc\u05d5\u05da}}) whilst he was serving in the [[British Army]] in [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]].<ref name=SHT/> The two married in 1925.<ref name=SHT/><ref name=David/> As Aharon Bloch was a naturalised citizen of the United Kingdom, this gave Dora British citizenship.<ref name=SHT/><ref name=David>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NgbABQAAQBAJ&pg=PT105|title=Operation Thunderbolt: Flight 139 and the Raid on Entebbe Airport, the Most Audacious Hostage Rescue Mission in History|first=Saul|last=David|publisher=Hachette|year=2015|isbn=1444762524|page=105}}</ref> They had three sons.<ref name=ap/>  In 1976 she was a grandmother and a widow living in [[Tel Aviv]].<ref name=BBC>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/july/7/newsid_2496000/2496095.stm| title= 1976: British grandmother missing in Uganda| work=[[BBC News]]| accessdate=5 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Disappearance==\n[[File:Flickr - Government Press Office (GPO) - Ilan Har Tuv.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Ilan Hartuv, Dora Bloch's son with whom she had been travelling.]]\nOn 27 June 1976, Bloch, aged 74<ref name=BBC/><ref name=npr/> or 75,<ref name=JTA/> was on Air France Flight 139, an [[Airbus A300]] plane, travelling to [[New York City]] for her youngest son Daniel's wedding.<ref name=BBC/><ref name=NYT>{{cite news| url= https://www.nytimes.com/1979/06/06/archives/leaders-of-israel-attend-funeral-of-dora-bloch-victim-of-idi-amin.html?_r=0| title= Leaders of Israel Attend Funeral Of Dora Bloch, Victim of Idi Amin| work=[[The New York Times]]| date=6 June 1979| accessdate=5 March 2017}}</ref> The flight was hijacked by terrorists after a stopover in Athens and was redirected to [[Entebbe]], Uganda.<ref name=npr/> With her fluency in languages, Bloch served as an interpreter between the hostages and hijackers.<ref name=ap/><ref name=SHT>{{cite news| url= https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1755&dat=19760714&id=8OQhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=OGcEAAAAIBAJ&pg=4259,5631759&hl=en| title= Family, Friends Describe Dora Bloch| work=[[Sarasota Herald-Tribune]]| date=14 July 1976| accessdate=11 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nBloch became ill on the plane and was transferred to [[Mulago Hospital]] in [[Kampala]].<ref name=Nation/> She is believed to have choked on food, and [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]] papers say that she was also being treated for [[Venous ulcer|leg ulcers]] while at the hospital.<ref name=Independent/><ref name=SAHO>{{cite web| url=http://www.sahistory.org.za/dated-event/cruel-murder-dora-bloch| title= Cruel murder of Dora Bloch| publisher=South African History Online| accessdate=5 March 2017}}</ref> Bloch's son Ilan Hartuv, who was released during the subsequent [[Operation Entebbe]] [[counter-terrorist]] hostage-rescue mission,<ref name=BBC/> was able to speak to a Ugandan doctor about his mother's health.<ref name=Nation>{{cite news| url= https://www.nation.co.ke/news/Entebbe-raid-embarrassed-Amin--nearly-caused-East-African-war/1056-3277804-1327oaiz/index.html| title= Entebbe raid humiliated Amin, nearly caused East African war| last=Kalinaki| first=Daniel K. | work=[[Daily Nation]]| date=3 July 2016| accessdate=3 February 2019}}</ref> [[Henry Kyemba]], then Uganda's Minister of Health, said that he had allowed Bloch to stay in hospital for an extra night before being returned to the other hostages.<ref name=CT>{{cite news| url=http://archives.chicagotribune.com/1977/06/19/page/43/article/the-killing-of-dora-bloch| title=The Killing of Dora Bloch| work=Chicago Tribune| date=19 June 1977| accessdate=5 March 2017}}</ref> As a result of this, Bloch was not with the other hostages, and so was not freed during the Operation Entebbe raid.<ref name=David/>\n\nDuring Operation Entebbe, Bloch's family in Israel were taken to the [[HaKirya]] military complex in [[Tel Aviv]], before going to the airport. Once at the airport, they were told that Bloch was still in Uganda.<ref name=TOI>{{cite news| url= https://www.timesofisrael.com/at-entebbe-with-the-relatives-of-two-who-never-made-it-back-home/| title= At Entebbe, with the relatives of two who never made it back home| last=Ahren| first=Raphael|work=[[The Times of Israel]]| date=4 July 2016| accessdate=6 March 2019}}</ref> They spent an hour in [[Shiva (Judaism)|shiva]], but no longer as she was not confirmed dead.<ref name=TOI/>\n\nOn 4 July, the British Government were informed that Bloch was not among the hostages released during Operation Entebbe.<ref name=Parliament>{{cite web| url= https://api.parliament.uk/historic-hansard/commons/1976/jul/07/uganda-mrs-dora-bloch| title= Uganda (Mrs. Dora Bloch)| publisher=[[House of Commons]]| date=7 July 1976| accessdate=6 March 2019}}</ref> As a result, she was visited by [[James Hennessy]], then-[[List of High Commissioners of the United Kingdom to Uganda|High Commissioner of the United Kingdom to Uganda]],<ref name=Independent/><ref name=Parliament/> and Peter Chandley, second secretary of the [[British High Commission]] in Kampala.<ref name=David/><ref name=NYT76>{{cite news| url= https://www.nytimes.com/1976/07/14/archives/body-of-mrs-bloch-said-to-heen-been-seen-in-a-forest-in-uganda.html| title= Body of Mrs. Bloch Said to Have Been Seen in a Forest in Uganda| work=[[The New York Times]]| date=14 July 1976| accessdate=2 February 2019}}</ref> Bloch told Chandley that she had been treated well in the hospital, but did not like the food.<ref name=David/> They were also told that Bloch was going to be moved to the [[Grand Imperial Hotel]] in Kampala.<ref name=Parliament/> Chandley and his wife went to get some food for Bloch, but when they returned, they were denied entry to the hospital.<ref name=David/><ref name=Parliament/> The reason for this was that four men including [[Farouk Minawa]], head of the [[State Research Bureau (organisation)|State Research Bureau]] (Ugandan secret police) and [[Idi Amin]]'s Chief of Protocol [[Nasur Ondoga]] had taken Bloch from her hospital bed and murdered her.<ref name=David/><ref name=BBC/> The policeman guarding Bloch was also killed.<ref name=BBC/><ref name=Independent/><ref name=SAHO/><ref name=CT/>\n\n==Aftermath==\n\nA Ugandan police search did not find Bloch, and the Ugandan government informed the UK that they \"had no responsibility\" for Bloch after Operation Entebbe.<ref name=Parliament/> In early July, a Ugandan traveller reported seeing a body, which he believed to be Bloch, near a group of Ugandan soldiers,<ref name=JTA>{{cite news| url= https://www.jta.org/1976/07/14/archive/mrs-bloch-is-dead-to-the-best-knowledge-of-british-government| title=Mrs. Bloch is Dead, to the Best Knowledge of British Government| work=[[Jewish Telegraphic Agency]]| date=14 July 1976| accessdate=11 February 2019}}</ref><ref name=NYT76/> around {{convert|11|mi|km}} from Kampala.<ref name=JTA/> On 9 July, the [[United Nations]] debated the Entebbe hijacking incident. The United Kingdom suggested a resolution that condemned both the hijack and the loss of life, so as not to endanger the lives of Britons in Uganda, including Bloch.<ref name=David/> During the debate, the Ugandan government reiterated their claim that Bloch had been returned to Entebbe airport.<ref name=David/><ref name=NYT76/><ref name=EA>{{cite news| url= https://www.theeastafrican.co.ke/magazine/434746-619406-eaftpk/index.html| title= Fallout over raid on Entebbe| work=[[The EastAfrican]]| date=6 July 2009| accessdate=2 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 July, [[Minister of State (United Kingdom)|Minister of State]] for the Foreign and Commonwealth Office [[Ted Rowlands, Baron Rowlands|Ted Rowlands]] said that Bloch was presumed dead.<ref name=BBC/><ref name=JTA/> On 15 July, the British Government demanded a full search for \"Bloch or her body\", a request that was never fulfilled.<ref>{{cite web| url= https://api.parliament.uk/historic-hansard/written-answers/1977/jan/13/uganda-mrs-dora-bloch#S5CV0923P0_19770113_CWA_107| title= Uganda (Mrs. Dora Bloch)| publisher=[[House of Commons]]| date=13 January 1977| accessdate=6 March 2019}}</ref> A suggested motive for her killing was retaliation for the deaths of 50 Ugandan soldiers during Operation Entebbe.<ref name=Independent/> Amin later expelled Chandley from the High Commission, alleging that he was pro-Israeli and had supported the death of Ugandan troops.<ref name=NYT76/>\n\nAs a result of Bloch's disappearance, Britain withdrew their High Commissioner to Uganda,<ref name=Independent/> and on 28 July, Britain cut all diplomatic ties with Uganda.<ref name=Independent/><ref name=BBC/><ref name=Theakston/> It was the first time in 30 years that Britain had severed ties with a [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]] country.<ref name=BBC/><ref name=Theakston>{{cite book| url= https://books.google.com/books?id=guuQAgAAQBAJ&dq=uk+cuts+diplomatic+ties+with+uganda+1976&source=gbs_navlinks_s| title= British Foreign Secretaries Since 1974| last=Theakston| first=Kevin| publisher=[[Routledge]]| page=75| date=August 2004| access-date=5 March 2017}}</ref> The British Government said that the main reason for cutting ties was the disappearance of Bloch, although other events during Amin's leadership had also contributed.<ref name=Makubuya>{{cite book| url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ETeEDwAAQBAJ&dq=dora+bloch&source=gbs_navlinks_s| title=Protection, Patronage, or Plunder? British Machinations and (B)uganda\u2019s Struggle for Independence|last=Makubuya| first=Apollo| publisher=Cambridge Scholars Publishing| pages=358\u2013359| date=January 2019| access-date=6 March 2019}}</ref> In retaliation, Amin declared himself the \"Conqueror of the British Empire (CBE)\", and the unofficial King of Scotland. He added \"Conqueror of the British Empire\" to his list of official titles.<ref name=Makubuya/><ref name=Appiah>{{cite book|last1=Appiah|first1=Anthony|last2=Gates| first2=Henry Lewis|title=Africana: The Encyclopedia of the African and African American Experience|url=https://archive.org/details/africanaencyclop00appi|url-access=registration|date=1999}}</ref> After the fall of Amin in 1979, Britain recommenced diplomatic relations with Uganda.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/C15798| title= Foreign and Commonwealth Office: High Commission, Uganda: Registered Files| publisher=[[The National Archives (United Kingdom)|The National Archives]]| accessdate=11 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1987, Kyemba said that Bloch had been dragged from her hospital bed and murdered by members of the Ugandan Army loyal to Amin.<ref name=BBC/> Declassified British documents released in February 2007 confirmed that Bloch had been killed on Amin's orders. According to the documents, a Ugandan citizen told the British High Commissioner in Kampala that Bloch had been shot and her body deposited into the trunk of a car with Ugandan intelligence services number plates. The documents also showed that Britain continued to press Amin for information on Bloch's whereabouts, and that Amin continually denied knowledge of her fate.<ref name=npr>{{cite web |url=http://www.nrg.co.il/online/1/ART1/543/265.html|title=\u05db\u05da \u05d4\u05d5\u05e8\u05d4 \u05d0\u05d9\u05d3\u05d9 \u05d0\u05de\u05d9\u05df \u05dc\u05e8\u05e6\u05d5\u05d7 \u05d0\u05ea \u05d3\u05d5\u05e8\u05d4 \u05d1\u05dc\u05d5\u05da|language=Hebrew|trans-title=So Idi Amin Ordered the Murder of Dora Bloch|first=Yael|last=Arava|date=13 February 2007|accessdate=5 March 2017|work=[[Maariv (newspaper)|Maariv]]}}</ref><ref name=Independent>{{cite news| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/revealed-the-fate-of-idi-amins-hijack-victim-436181.html| title= Revealed: the fate of Idi Amin's hijack victim| last=Verkaik| first=Robert| work=[[The Independent]]| year=2007| accessdate=5 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Recovery of body===\n[[File:HarHamenuchotFromGivhatShaul.JPG|thumb|200px|right|Har Hamenuchot, where Dora Bloch is buried.]]\n\nAfter the [[Uganda\u2013Tanzania War]],<ref name=EA/> Tanzanian troops discovered Bloch's body in 1979 in a [[sugar plantation]] around {{convert|20|mi|km}} from [[Kampala]],<ref name=BBC/><ref name=NYT/> near to the [[Kampala\u2013Jinja Highway|Jinja Road]].<ref name=David/> Visual identification was impossible because her face was badly burned, but the corpse showed signs of a leg ulcer.<ref name=npr/><ref name=Independent/> A pathologist working with the [[Israel Defense Forces]] formally identified Bloch from the remains.<ref name=TOI/> Her remains were returned to her son in Israel,<ref name=NYT/> where she was given an Israeli [[state funeral]].<ref name=David/><ref name=BBC/><ref name=NYT/><ref>{{cite news| url= http://archive.jta.org/1979/06/05/archive/dora-blochs-remains-to-be-buried| title= Dora Bloch's Remains to Be Buried| work=[[Jewish Telegraphic Agency]]| date=5 June 1979| accessdate=5 March 2017}}</ref> She was buried in Jerusalem's Mount of Quietudes.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1979/06/04/archives/body-of-amin-victim-is-flown-back-to-israel.html ''The New York Times'']</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bloch, Dora}}\n[[Category:1976 deaths]]\n[[Category:1976 murders in Africa]]\n[[Category:Operation Entebbe]]\n[[Category:British murder victims]]\n[[Category:Israeli murder victims]]\n[[Category:People from Jaffa]]\n[[Category:People from Tel Aviv]]\n[[Category:Deaths by person]]\n[[Category:People murdered in Uganda]]\n[[Category:Israeli people murdered abroad]]\n[[Category:British people murdered abroad]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Uganda]]\n[[Category:Uganda\u2013United Kingdom relations]]\n[[Category:Female murder victims]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Hostage murdered after Operation Entebbe}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates| date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Dora Bloch\n| image         = Flickr - Government Press Office (GPO) - Dora Bloch's Family Pays Last Respects.jpg\n| alt           =\n| caption       = Family members at the grave of Dora Bloch\n| birth_name    = Dora Feinberg\n| birth_date    = 1901/2\n| birth_place   = [[Jaffa]], [[Ottoman Empire]]\n| death_date    = 1976 (aged 74/75)\n| death_place   = [[Kampala]], Uganda\n| burial_place  = [[Har HaMenuchot]]\n| nationality   = British-Israeli\n| other_names   = Devorah Bloch\n| spouse        = Aharon Bloch\n| children      = 3\n| occupation    =\n| years_active  =\n| known_for     = Killed on order of [[Idi Amin]] after [[Operation Entebbe]]\n}}\n\nIn June 1976, '''Dora Bloch''' ({{Lang-he|\u05d3\u05d5\u05e8\u05d4 \u05d1\u05dc\u05d5\u05da}}), a dual Israeli-British citizen, was a hostage on Air France Flight 139 from [[Tel Aviv]] to Paris, which was hijacked after a stopover in [[Athens]] and rerouted to [[Entebbe]], Uganda. Bloch became ill on the plane and was taken to a hospital in [[Kampala]]; she was not rescued with the other hostages during [[Operation Entebbe]], but went missing from the hospital. Her disappearance led to Britain cutting diplomatic ties with Uganda. Her body was discovered in 1979 in a sugar plantation near the capital. In February 2007, declassified British documents confirmed that she was killed on the order of [[Idi Amin]].\n\n==Biography==\nDora Feinberg was born in [[Jaffa]], then a part of the [[Mutasarrifate of Jerusalem]], [[Ottoman Empire]] and now a part of Israel.<ref name=ap/><ref name=SHT/> Her father, Joseph Feinberg, was among the founders of the Jewish agricultural settlement of [[Rishon LeZion]].<ref name=ap/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rishonlezion.muni.il/eng/Pages/HistoryofRishonLeZion.aspx|title=History of Rishon LeZion|publisher=[[Rishon LeZion]] Municipality|accessdate=5 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170320162853/http://www.rishonlezion.muni.il/eng/pages/historyofrishonlezion.aspx|archive-date=20 March 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> After her father's death, she was raised by an uncle in Egypt. She moved to Jerusalem as an adult.<ref name=David/> She spoke Hebrew, Arabic, Russian, German, Italian, and English.<ref name=ap>{{cite news |url=http://archives.chicagotribune.com/1976/07/15/page/2/article/hostage-auntie-bloch-loved-kids|title=Hostage 'Auntie' Bloch Loved Kids|author=Associated Press|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=15 July 1976|accessdate=5 March 2017|page=2}}</ref> In 1920, she met Aharon Bloch ({{Lang-he|\u05d0\u05d4\u05e8\u05d5\u05df \u05d0\u05d4\u05e8\u05df \u05d1\u05dc\u05d5\u05da}}) whilst he was serving in the [[British Army]] in [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]].<ref name=SHT/> The two married in 1925.<ref name=SHT/><ref name=David/> As Aharon Bloch was a naturalised citizen of the United Kingdom, this gave Dora British citizenship.<ref name=SHT/><ref name=David>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NgbABQAAQBAJ&pg=PT105|title=Operation Thunderbolt: Flight 139 and the Raid on Entebbe Airport, the Most Audacious Hostage Rescue Mission in History|first=Saul|last=David|publisher=Hachette|year=2015|isbn=1444762524|page=105}}</ref> They had three sons.<ref name=ap/>  In 1976 she was a grandmother and a widow living in [[Tel Aviv]].<ref name=BBC>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/july/7/newsid_2496000/2496095.stm| title= 1976: British grandmother missing in Uganda| work=[[BBC News]]| accessdate=5 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Disappearance==\n[[File:Flickr - Government Press Office (GPO) - Ilan Har Tuv.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Ilan Hartuv, Dora Bloch's son with whom she had been travelling.]]\nOn 27 June 1976, Bloch, aged 74<ref name=BBC/><ref name=npr/> or 75,<ref name=JTA/> was on Air France Flight 139, an [[Airbus A300]] plane, travelling to [[New York City]] for her youngest son Daniel's wedding.<ref name=BBC/><ref name=NYT>{{cite news| url= https://www.nytimes.com/1979/06/06/archives/leaders-of-israel-attend-funeral-of-dora-bloch-victim-of-idi-amin.html?_r=0| title= Leaders of Israel Attend Funeral Of Dora Bloch, Victim of Idi Amin| work=[[The New York Times]]| date=6 June 1979| accessdate=5 March 2017}}</ref> The flight was hijacked by terrorists after a stopover in Athens and was redirected to [[Entebbe]], Uganda.<ref name=npr/> With her fluency in languages, Bloch served as an interpreter between the hostages and hijackers.<ref name=ap/><ref name=SHT>{{cite news| url= https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1755&dat=19760714&id=8OQhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=OGcEAAAAIBAJ&pg=4259,5631759&hl=en| title= Family, Friends Describe Dora Bloch| work=[[Sarasota Herald-Tribune]]| date=14 July 1976| accessdate=11 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nBloch became ill on the plane and was transferred to [[Mulago Hospital]] in [[Kampala]].<ref name=Nation/> She is believed to have choked on food, and [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]] papers say that she was also being treated for [[Venous ulcer|leg ulcers]] while at the hospital.<ref name=Independent/><ref name=SAHO>{{cite web| url=http://www.sahistory.org.za/dated-event/cruel-murder-dora-bloch| title= Cruel murder of Dora Bloch| publisher=South African History Online| accessdate=5 March 2017}}</ref> Bloch's son Ilan Hartuv, who was released during the subsequent [[Operation Entebbe]] [[counter-terrorist]] hostage-rescue mission,<ref name=BBC/> was able to speak to a Ugandan doctor about his mother's health.<ref name=Nation>{{cite news| url= https://www.nation.co.ke/news/Entebbe-raid-embarrassed-Amin--nearly-caused-East-African-war/1056-3277804-1327oaiz/index.html| title= Entebbe raid humiliated Amin, nearly caused East African war| last=Kalinaki| first=Daniel K. | work=[[Daily Nation]]| date=3 July 2016| accessdate=3 February 2019}}</ref> [[Henry Kyemba]], then Uganda's Minister of Health, said that he had allowed Bloch to stay in hospital for an extra night before being returned to the other hostages.<ref name=CT>{{cite news| url=http://archives.chicagotribune.com/1977/06/19/page/43/article/the-killing-of-dora-bloch| title=The Killing of Dora Bloch| work=Chicago Tribune| date=19 June 1977| accessdate=5 March 2017}}</ref> As a result of this, Bloch was not with the other hostages, and so was not freed during the Operation Entebbe raid.<ref name=David/>\n\nDuring Operation Entebbe, Bloch's family in Israel were taken to the [[HaKirya]] military complex in [[Tel Aviv]], before going to the airport. Once at the airport, they were told that Bloch was still in Uganda.<ref name=TOI>{{cite news| url= https://www.timesofisrael.com/at-entebbe-with-the-relatives-of-two-who-never-made-it-back-home/| title= At Entebbe, with the relatives of two who never made it back home| last=Ahren| first=Raphael|work=[[The Times of Israel]]| date=4 July 2016| accessdate=6 March 2019}}</ref> They spent an hour in [[Shiva (Judaism)|shiva]], but no longer as she was not confirmed dead.<ref name=TOI/>\n\nOn 4 July, the British Government were informed that Bloch was not among the hostages released during Operation Entebbe.<ref name=Parliament>{{cite web| url= https://api.parliament.uk/historic-hansard/commons/1976/jul/07/uganda-mrs-dora-bloch| title= Uganda (Mrs. Dora Bloch)| publisher=[[House of Commons]]| date=7 July 1976| accessdate=6 March 2019}}</ref> As a result, she was visited by [[James Hennessy]], then-[[List of High Commissioners of the United Kingdom to Uganda|High Commissioner of the United Kingdom to Uganda]],<ref name=Independent/><ref name=Parliament/> and Peter Chandley, second secretary of the [[British High Commission]] in Kampala.<ref name=David/><ref name=NYT76>{{cite news| url= https://www.nytimes.com/1976/07/14/archives/body-of-mrs-bloch-said-to-heen-been-seen-in-a-forest-in-uganda.html| title= Body of Mrs. Bloch Said to Have Been Seen in a Forest in Uganda| work=[[The New York Times]]| date=14 July 1976| accessdate=2 February 2019}}</ref> Bloch told Chandley that she had been treated well in the hospital, but did not like the food.<ref name=David/> They were also told that Bloch was going to be moved to the [[Grand Imperial Hotel]] in Kampala.<ref name=Parliament/> Chandley and his wife went to get some food for Bloch, but when they returned, they were denied entry to the hospital.<ref name=David/><ref name=Parliament/> The reason for this was that four men including [[Farouk Minawa]], head of the [[State Research Bureau (organisation)|State Research Bureau]] (Ugandan secret police) and [[Idi Amin]]'s Chief of Protocol [[Nasur Ondoga]] had taken Bloch from her hospital bed and murdered her.<ref name=David/><ref name=BBC/> The policeman guarding Bloch was also killed.<ref name=BBC/><ref name=Independent/><ref name=SAHO/><ref name=CT/>\n\n==Aftermath==\n\nAn Ugandan police search did not find Bloch, and the Ugandan government informed the UK that they \"had no responsibility\" for Bloch after Operation Entebbe.<ref name=Parliament/> In early July, a Ugandan traveller reported seeing a body, which he believed to be Bloch, near a group of Ugandan soldiers,<ref name=JTA>{{cite news| url= https://www.jta.org/1976/07/14/archive/mrs-bloch-is-dead-to-the-best-knowledge-of-british-government| title=Mrs. Bloch is Dead, to the Best Knowledge of British Government| work=[[Jewish Telegraphic Agency]]| date=14 July 1976| accessdate=11 February 2019}}</ref><ref name=NYT76/> around {{convert|11|mi|km}} from Kampala.<ref name=JTA/> On 9 July, the [[United Nations]] debated the Entebbe hijacking incident. The United Kingdom suggested a resolution that condemned both the hijack and the loss of life, so as not to endanger the lives of Britons in Uganda, including Bloch.<ref name=David/> During the debate, the Ugandan government reiterated their claim that Bloch had been returned to Entebbe airport.<ref name=David/><ref name=NYT76/><ref name=EA>{{cite news| url= https://www.theeastafrican.co.ke/magazine/434746-619406-eaftpk/index.html| title= Fallout over raid on Entebbe| work=[[The EastAfrican]]| date=6 July 2009| accessdate=2 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 July, [[Minister of State (United Kingdom)|Minister of State]] for the Foreign and Commonwealth Office [[Ted Rowlands, Baron Rowlands|Ted Rowlands]] said that Bloch was presumed dead.<ref name=BBC/><ref name=JTA/> On 15 July, the British Government demanded a full search for \"Bloch or her body\", a request that was never fulfilled.<ref>{{cite web| url= https://api.parliament.uk/historic-hansard/written-answers/1977/jan/13/uganda-mrs-dora-bloch#S5CV0923P0_19770113_CWA_107| title= Uganda (Mrs. Dora Bloch)| publisher=[[House of Commons]]| date=13 January 1977| accessdate=6 March 2019}}</ref> A suggested motive for her killing was retaliation for the deaths of 50 Ugandan soldiers during Operation Entebbe.<ref name=Independent/> Amin later expelled Chandley from the High Commission, alleging that he was pro-Israeli and had supported the death of Ugandan troops.<ref name=NYT76/>\n\nAs a result of Bloch's disappearance, Britain withdrew their High Commissioner to Uganda,<ref name=Independent/> and on 28 July, Britain cut all diplomatic ties with Uganda.<ref name=Independent/><ref name=BBC/><ref name=Theakston/> It was the first time in 30 years that Britain had severed ties with a [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]] country.<ref name=BBC/><ref name=Theakston>{{cite book| url= https://books.google.com/books?id=guuQAgAAQBAJ&dq=uk+cuts+diplomatic+ties+with+uganda+1976&source=gbs_navlinks_s| title= British Foreign Secretaries Since 1974| last=Theakston| first=Kevin| publisher=[[Routledge]]| page=75| date=August 2004| access-date=5 March 2017}}</ref> The British Government said that the main reason for cutting ties was the disappearance of Bloch, although other events during Amin's leadership had also contributed.<ref name=Makubuya>{{cite book| url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ETeEDwAAQBAJ&dq=dora+bloch&source=gbs_navlinks_s| title=Protection, Patronage, or Plunder? British Machinations and (B)uganda\u2019s Struggle for Independence|last=Makubuya| first=Apollo| publisher=Cambridge Scholars Publishing| pages=358\u2013359| date=January 2019| access-date=6 March 2019}}</ref> In retaliation, Amin declared himself the \"Conqueror of the British Empire (CBE)\", and the unofficial King of Scotland. He added \"Conqueror of the British Empire\" to his list of official titles.<ref name=Makubuya/><ref name=Appiah>{{cite book|last1=Appiah|first1=Anthony|last2=Gates| first2=Henry Lewis|title=Africana: The Encyclopedia of the African and African American Experience|url=https://archive.org/details/africanaencyclop00appi|url-access=registration|date=1999}}</ref> After the fall of Amin in 1979, Britain recommenced diplomatic relations with Uganda.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/C15798| title= Foreign and Commonwealth Office: High Commission, Uganda: Registered Files| publisher=[[The National Archives (United Kingdom)|The National Archives]]| accessdate=11 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1987, Kyemba said that Bloch had been dragged from her hospital bed and murdered by members of the Ugandan Army loyal to Amin.<ref name=BBC/> Declassified British documents released in February 2007 confirmed that Bloch had been killed on Amin's orders. According to the documents, a Ugandan citizen told the British High Commissioner in Kampala that Bloch had been shot and her body deposited into the trunk of a car with Ugandan intelligence services number plates. The documents also showed that Britain continued to press Amin for information on Bloch's whereabouts, and that Amin continually denied knowledge of her fate.<ref name=npr>{{cite web |url=http://www.nrg.co.il/online/1/ART1/543/265.html|title=\u05db\u05da \u05d4\u05d5\u05e8\u05d4 \u05d0\u05d9\u05d3\u05d9 \u05d0\u05de\u05d9\u05df \u05dc\u05e8\u05e6\u05d5\u05d7 \u05d0\u05ea \u05d3\u05d5\u05e8\u05d4 \u05d1\u05dc\u05d5\u05da|language=Hebrew|trans-title=So Idi Amin Ordered the Murder of Dora Bloch|first=Yael|last=Arava|date=13 February 2007|accessdate=5 March 2017|work=[[Maariv (newspaper)|Maariv]]}}</ref><ref name=Independent>{{cite news| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/revealed-the-fate-of-idi-amins-hijack-victim-436181.html| title= Revealed: the fate of Idi Amin's hijack victim| last=Verkaik| first=Robert| work=[[The Independent]]| year=2007| accessdate=5 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Recovery of body===\n[[File:HarHamenuchotFromGivhatShaul.JPG|thumb|200px|right|Har Hamenuchot, where Dora Bloch is buried.]]\n\nAfter the [[Uganda\u2013Tanzania War]],<ref name=EA/> Tanzanian troops discovered Bloch's body in 1979 in a [[sugar plantation]] around {{convert|20|mi|km}} from [[Kampala]],<ref name=BBC/><ref name=NYT/> near to the [[Kampala\u2013Jinja Highway|Jinja Road]].<ref name=David/> Visual identification was impossible because her face was badly burned, but the corpse showed signs of a leg ulcer.<ref name=npr/><ref name=Independent/> A pathologist working with the [[Israel Defense Forces]] formally identified Bloch from the remains.<ref name=TOI/> Her remains were returned to her son in Israel,<ref name=NYT/> where she was given an Israeli [[state funeral]].<ref name=David/><ref name=BBC/><ref name=NYT/><ref>{{cite news| url= http://archive.jta.org/1979/06/05/archive/dora-blochs-remains-to-be-buried| title= Dora Bloch's Remains to Be Buried| work=[[Jewish Telegraphic Agency]]| date=5 June 1979| accessdate=5 March 2017}}</ref> She was buried in Jerusalem's Mount of Quietudes.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1979/06/04/archives/body-of-amin-victim-is-flown-back-to-israel.html ''The New York Times'']</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bloch, Dora}}\n[[Category:1976 deaths]]\n[[Category:1976 murders in Africa]]\n[[Category:Operation Entebbe]]\n[[Category:British murder victims]]\n[[Category:Israeli murder victims]]\n[[Category:People from Jaffa]]\n[[Category:People from Tel Aviv]]\n[[Category:Deaths by person]]\n[[Category:People murdered in Uganda]]\n[[Category:Israeli people murdered abroad]]\n[[Category:British people murdered abroad]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Uganda]]\n[[Category:Uganda\u2013United Kingdom relations]]\n[[Category:Female murder victims]]\n", "name_user": "Transphasic", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAftermath", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Murder_of_Dora_Bloch"}
{"title_page": "Uniqlo", "text_new": "{{short description|Japanese casual wear designer, manufacturer and retailer}}\n{{more footnotes|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Uniqlo Co., Ltd.<br>\u682a\u5f0f\u4f1a\u793e\u30e6\u30cb\u30af\u30ed\n| native_name_lang = ja\n| logo = UNIQLO logo.svg\n| logo_caption = Uniqlo logo\n| type = [[subsidiary|Wholly owned subsidiary]]\n| hq_location_country = Japan\n| key_people = [[Tadashi Yanai]] <small>(Chairman, President & CEO)</small><br />Takahiro Wakabayashi <small>(Senior Vice President)</small>\n| industry = [[Fashion]]<br />[[Retail]] \n| products = [[Clothing]]\n| operating_income =\n| net_income =\n| num_employees = 44,424 (2018)\n| parent = [[Fast Retailing]] <br>(2005\u2013present)\n| subsid =\n| homepage = [http://www.uniqlo.com/ uniqlo.com]\n| footnotes =\n| foundation = [[Ube, Yamaguchi|Ube]], [[Yamaguchi Prefecture|Yamaguchi]], [[Japan]]<br>{{start date and age|1949}}\n| location = [[Midtown Tower]], [[Akasaka, Tokyo|Akasaka]]<br>9-chome, [[Minato, Tokyo|Minato]], [[Tokyo]]\n}}\n\n{{Nihongo|'''Uniqlo<!--\"Uniqlo\" lowercase per [[WP:MOSTM]] guide--> Co., Ltd.'''|\u682a\u5f0f\u4f1a\u793e\u30e6\u30cb\u30af\u30ed|Kabushiki-gaisha Yunikuro}} ({{IPAc-en|US|\u02c8|ju\u02d0|n|i|k|l|o\u028a}} {{respell|YOO|nee|kloh}};<ref name=\"japansoc\"/> {{IPA-ja|j\u026f\u0272ik\u026f\u027eo|language}}) is a [[Economy of Japan|Japanese]] [[casual wear]] designer, manufacturer and [[retail]]er.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uniqlo.com/uk/en/company/|title=About Uniqlo {{!}} UNIQLO|website=www.uniqlo.com|language=en|access-date=2018-03-11|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The company is a wholly owned subsidiary of [[Fast Retailing|Fast Retailing Co., Ltd.]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fastretailing.com/eng/group/|title=Group Companies {{!}} FAST RETAILING CO., LTD.|website=www.fastretailing.com|language=en|access-date=2018-03-11|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Uniqlo Shinsaibashisuji Flag ship store Interior view 2014.jpg|thumb|upright|Uniqlo flagship store in Shinsaibashisuji, Osaka]]\n\n===Origins in Japan===\nA Yamaguchi-based company, Ogori Sh\u014dji (which, until then, had been operating men's clothing shops called \"Men's Shop OS\") was founded in March 1949 in [[Ube, Yamaguchi]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fastretailing.com/eng/about/history/|title=1949-2003 {{!}} FAST RETAILING CO., LTD.|website=www.fastretailing.com|language=en|access-date=2018-03-11|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn May 1984, it opened a unisex casual wear store in Fukuro-machi, [[Naka-ku, Hiroshima|Naka-ku]], [[Hiroshima]] under the name \"Unique Clothing Warehouse\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=White|first1=Gillian B.|title=Why Urban Millennials Love Uniqlo|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2019/04/uniqlo-millennials-gap/583219/|website=The Atlantic|access-date=14 March 2019|date=13 March 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Initially, the brand was going to be registered as a shortened contraction of \"unique clothing\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://asia.nikkei.com/Business/Uniqlos-Hong-Kong-role-models-are-failing-the-test-of-time|title=Uniqlo's Hong Kong role models are failing the test of time|last=Kawase|first=Kenji|date=2014-10-23|website=Nikkei Asian Review|language=en-GB|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=2019-05-28|df=dmy-all}}</ref> However, in 1988, during administration work in Hong Kong for registering the brand, staff in charge of registration misread the \"C\" as \"Q\", and that is how the brand name was born.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://toni-marino.com/uniqlo-logo/|title=UNIQLO Logo Designed By Kashiwa Sato|date=2018-07-26|website=Toni Marino|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref> Tadashi Yanai then changed the store name to \"uniqlo\" across Japan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mpfinance.com/htm/finance/20130426/news/ea_eaa3.htm|script-title=ja:\u5beb\u932f\u516c\u53f8\u540d \u5c07\u932f\u5c31\u932f\u4f5c\u54c1\u724c|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151127084446/http://www.mpfinance.com/htm/finance/20130426/news/ea_eaa3.htm|archive-date=27 November 2015|website=mpfinance.com|language=ja|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In September 1991, the name of the company was changed from \"Ogori Sh\u014dji\" to \"Fast Retailing\", and by April 1994, there were over 100 Uniqlo stores operating throughout Japan.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\n===Private-label strategy===\nIn 1997, Fast Retailing adopted a set of strategies from American retailer [[Gap Inc.|The Gap]], known as \"SPA\" (for specialty-store/retailer of private-label apparel), meaning that they would produce their own clothing and sell it exclusively.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}} They engaged the retail brand consultancy, CIA, Inc. / The Brand Architect Group, to guide the company through the realization of this strategy, including consulting on merchandise, visual merchandising and display, store design and a new logo designed by Richard Seireeni and Sy Chen of The Brand Architect Group's Los Angeles office.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}} Uniqlo had begun outsourcing their clothing manufacturing to factories in China where labour was cheap, a well-established corporate practice.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}} Japan was in the depths of a recession at the time, and the low-cost goods proved popular.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theculturetrip.com/asia/japan/articles/a-history-of-uniqlo-in-1-minute/|title=A History Of Uniqlo In 1 Minute|last=Joy|first=Alicia|website=Culture Trip|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref> Their advertising campaigns, clothing quality and new retail layouts also proved fruitful.<ref>{{cite news|last=Nagata|first=Kazuaki|url=http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/nn20091117i1.html|title=Choice, chic, cheap \u2014 no one feels fleeced|work=[[Japan Times]]|page=3|date=2009-11-17|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n{{rquote|right|In creating its clothing lines, Uniqlo embraces both ''shun'' and ''kino-bi''. ''Shun'' [\u65ec] means 'timing, best timing, but also at the same time it's a trend,' something that's updated and just in time, neither early nor late. The company offers clothing basics, but basics that are current, that respond to what's going on today in art and design. ''Kino-bi'' [\u6a5f\u80fd\u7f8e] means function and beauty, joined together: the clothing is presented in an organized, rational manner, and that very organization and rationality creates an artistic pattern and rhythm. All these qualities reflect the defining characteristics of modern Japanese culture, modern '[[Nihonjinron|Japaneseness]].'|Nobuo&nbsp;Domae,&nbsp;CEO, Uniqlo USA (April&nbsp;2007)<ref name=\"japansoc\"/>}}\n\nIn November 1998, they opened their first urban Uniqlo store in [[Tokyo]]'s trendy [[Harajuku]] district, and outlets soon spread to major cities throughout Japan.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}} In 2001, sales turnover and gross profit reached a new peak, with over 500 retail stores in Japan.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}} When Uniqlo decided to expand overseas, it separated Uniqlo from the parent company,<ref name=\"japansoc\"/> and established Fast Retailing (Jiangsu) Apparel Co., Ltd. in China. In 2002 their first Chinese Uniqlo outlet was opened in [[Shanghai]] along with four overseas outlets in [[London]], England.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\n2005 saw more overseas expansion, with stores opening in the United States ([[New York City]]), Hong Kong ([[Tsim Sha Tsui]]) and South Korea ([[Seoul]]), their South Korean expansion being part of a joint venture with [[Lotte (conglomerate)|Lotte]].{{citation needed|date=October 2017}} As of year-end 2005, in addition to its overseas holdings, Uniqlo had around 700 stores within Japan.{{Citation needed|date=September 2009}} By 2006 sales were $4 billion.<ref name=\"japansoc\"/> By April 2007, the company had set a global sales goal of $10 billion and a ranking among the top five global retailers, joining what at the time was [[Gap (clothing retailer)|Gap]], [[H&M]], [[Inditex]], and [[Limited Brands]].<ref name=\"japansoc\"/>\n\nFast Retailing signed a design consulting contract for Uniqlo products with fashion designer [[Jil Sander]] in March 2009.<ref>[http://www.fastretailing.com/eng/about/history/2009.html 2009 | FAST RETAILING CO., LTD]. Fastretailing.com (2010-12-20). Retrieved on 2011-02-16.</ref> [[Shiatzy Chen]] has been approached by Uniqlo to produce a [[capsule collection]] of ready to wear pieces to launch in November 2010 while Asia's largest Uniqlo store outside Japan opened its doors in [[Kuala Lumpur]] in the same month.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\n[[File:Uniqlo jeans.jpg|thumb|Uniqlo jeans at their Tokyo store]]\n\nOn 2 September 2009, Fast Retailing announced that the company would target annual group sales of 5 trillion yen (approx. US$61.2 billion) and pretax profit from operations of 1 trillion yen (approx. US$12.2 billion) by 2020. This means that the company is aiming to become the world's biggest specialty retailer of private label apparel with a continuous growth rate of 20% per year. The figure breaks down as one trillion yen from Uniqlo's Japan business, three trillion yen from its international business, and one trillion yen from {{Clarify span|\"Japan-related and global brand business.\"|date=December 2012}}  The company's international business target breaks down as one trillion yen in China, one trillion in other Asian countries and one trillion in Europe and the United States.<ref>Kensuke Kojima (2011). ''Uniqlo Syndrome''. Toyo Keizai Shinpo Sha. {{ISBN|4-492-76191-8}} Tenkai Japan. ASIN: B004PYDPOK.</ref>\n\nIn October 2018, Uniqlo collaborated with designer [[Alexander Wang (designer)|Alexander Wang]] to create a line of Heattech layerable basics including tank tops, leggings, underwear and bodysuits.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://fashionista.com/2018/10/alexander-wang-uniqlo-heattech-collaboration-collection-prices|title=See Every Piece From the Alexander Wang x Uniqlo Heattech Collaboration|work=Fashionista|access-date=2018-11-16|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==International operations==\n[[File:Uniqlo world map.png|alt=|thumb|300x300px|Map of countries with Uniqlo stores]]\nAs of 30 November 2019, the company reported that 2249 Uniqlo stores were operational worldwide.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fastretailing.com/eng/group/shoplist/|title=Group Outlets {{!}} FAST RETAILING CO., LTD.|last=|first=|date=|website=fastretailing.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref>\n\n===Australia===\n[[File:Uniqlo, Murray Street, Perth, September 2018.jpg|thumb|right|Uniqlo in [[Perth]], [[Australia]]]]\nUniqlo opened its first Australian store in [[Melbourne]] in April 2014.<ref name=\"insideretail-au\"/> In 2015, it expanded into [[Queensland]], with the introduction of two shops in [[Brisbane]].<ref name=\"insideretail-au\">{{cite web|url=https://www.insideretail.com.au/blog/2015/09/01/uniqlo-to-launch-in-queensland/|title=Uniqlo heads to Queensland|date=1 September 2015|publisher=}}</ref> Uniqlo opened a shop in [[Chadstone Shopping Centre]] in [[Melbourne]], Victoria, the largest shopping centre in the southern hemisphere, in October 2016 when it was redeveloped.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uniqlo.com/au/shop/chadstone.html |title=Uniqlo Chadstone}}</ref> There are currently 22 stores in Australia, including in [[Sydney]] and [[Perth]]. There is also a Uniqlo store in the Eastland Shopping Centre in [[Ringwood]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uniqlo.com/au/shop/ |title=STORE LOCATOR - UNIQLO}}</ref>\n\n===Bangladesh===\nUniqlo started their first store at the [[New Elephant road]] in [[Dhaka]], [[Bangladesh]], on 5 July 2013. Uniqlo is known as Grameen Uniqlo there due to their social business concept JV with [[Grameen Bank]]. There are currently 15 stores in Dhaka, 1 store in [[Gazipur]] and 1 in [[Narsingdi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.grameenuniqlo.com/store-locator|title=Stores|date=19 July 2019|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Belgium===\nThe first Belgian Uniqlo store opened in October 2015 at [[Meir, Antwerp]].<ref>[http://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20170518_02887897 Uniqlo opent eerste winkel in hartje Brussel. De Standaard. 18/05/2017 at 10:34 by edm.]</ref> A second store followed suit at the [[Wijnegem Shopping Center]] on 25 March in the same year.<ref>[https://www.nieuwsblad.be/cnt/dmf20160308_02170904 Uniqlo opent op 25 maart in Wijnegem Shopping Center. Nieuwsblad. 08/03/2016 at 11:41 by inke.]</ref> 19 October 2017 saw the opening of a third store in [[Brussels]].<ref>Tine Stoop [http://marieclaire.be/nl/uniqlo-brussel-opening/ Uniqlo opent derde Belgische vestiging in Brussel] Marie Claire, 19 October 2017</ref>\n\n===Canada===\n[[File:UNIQLOEatonCenter.jpg|thumb|Uniqlo in Canada]]\nUniqlo opened their first Canadian store at the [[Toronto Eaton Centre]] on 30 September 2016, followed by a second store at the [[Yorkdale Shopping Centre]] on 20 October 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/life/2016/09/29/uniqlo-set-to-launch-first-canadian-store-at-the-eaton-centre.html| title=Uniqlo set to launch first Canadian store at the Eaton Centre|first=Leanne|last=Delap|date=2016-09-29|publisher=[[Toronto Star]]|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Measuring at 28,000 and 24,000 square feet, both stores are five times the size of the [[Muji]] store that opened in Toronto in 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/business/2016/06/19/uniqlo-targets-a-unique-apparel-market-everyone.html|title=Uniqlo targets a unique apparel market: Everyone|first=Francine|last=Kopun|date=2016-06-19|publisher=Toronto Star|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Three new stores in Ontario opened in 2018 at [[Vaughan Mills]], [[CF Markville]] and [[Square One Shopping Centre]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://dailyhive.com/toronto/toronto-uniqlo-announces-gta-opening-dates-2018|title=UNIQLO officially announces opening dates of its new GTA locations|last=Staff|first=DH Toronto|date=2018-08-29|work=Daily Hive|access-date=2018-10-26|language=en|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Uniqlo opened the new Oshawa location at the [[Oshawa Centre]] in March 2019 and opened the new Newmarket location at the [[Upper Canada Mall]] in April 2019, bringing the total number of stores in Ontario to seven.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.retail-insider.com/retail-insider/2019/1/uniqlo-ramps-up-canadian-expansion-with-2-store-announcements|title=Uniqlo Ramps Up Canadian Expansion with 2 Store Announcements|website=Retail Insider|language=en-CA|access-date=2019-01-22|df=dmy-all}}</ref> A third Canadian store, the first outside of Ontario and the first in Western Canada, opened at [[Burnaby]]'s [[Metropolis at Metrotown]] in October 2017 <ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.straight.com/life/977376/photos-uniqlo-finally-lands-west-coast-third-canadian-location| title=Photos: Uniqlo finally lands on West Coast with third Canadian location|first=Lucy|last=Lau|date=5 October 2017|publisher=[[The Georgia Straight]]}}</ref> to be followed by Surrey's [[Guildford Town Centre (mall)|Guildford Town Centre]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.guildfordtowncentre.com/stores/unisex-apparel-3/uniqlo-coming-soon/}}</ref> and [[Richmond Centre (mall)|Richmond Centre]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.richmond-news.com/news/uniqlo-coming-to-richmond-centre-1.23153895}}</ref> in Richmond, BC. A new store opened at [[Coquitlam Centre]] in Coquitlam, BC on 14 September 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straight.com/life/1126316/uniqlos-coquitlam-centre-location-opens-september-14|title=Uniqlo's Coquitlam Centre location opens on September 14|last=Lau|first=Lucy|date=2018-08-29|website=The Georgia Straight|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=2019-06-26|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://biv.com/article/2018/08/uniqlo-open-fourth-bc-store-coquitlam-centre|title=Uniqlo to open fourth B.C. store at Coquitlam Centre|last=Korstrom|first=Glen|date=|website=Business in Vancouver|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=2019-06-26|df=dmy-all}}</ref> A new [[West Edmonton Mall]] store opened on 27 September 2019.<ref>https://www.uniqlo.com/ca/en/information/press-release/2019/0604</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://edmonton.ctvnews.ca/this-popular-retailer-to-set-up-shop-in-west-edmonton-mall-1.4463528|title=This popular retailer to set up shop in West Edmonton Mall|last=|first=|date=2019-06-12|website=CTV News Edmonton|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=2019-06-26|df=dmy-all}}</ref> A new location is set to open at the [[Montreal Eaton Centre|Eaton Centre]] in Montreal in late 2020.\n\n===China===\n[[File:BJ Tour Beijing \u5317\u4eac \u4e09\u91cc\u5c6f Sanlitun Village shop UNIQLO mall facade visitors trees Aug-2010.JPG|thumb|right|Uniqlo in [[Sanlitun]], [[Beijing]], [[China]]]]\nUniqlo entered the [[Chinese mainland]] market in 2002. {{as of|August 2017}}, there were 555 stores in China, including in [[Beijing]], [[Guangzhou]], [[Chongqing]], [[Chengdu]], Nanjing, Ningbo, Shanghai, Shenzhen, Shijia, Tianjin and Xi'an.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fastretailing.com/eng/group/strategy/china.html|title=China - FAST RETAILING CO LTD|website=www.fastretailing.com}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2011, the magazine [[Bungeishunj\u016b|''Shukan Bunshun'']]{{clarify|date=July 2013|reason=is this same publication as \"Bungeishunj\u016b (magazine)\"?  if so, should link to wiki article on magazine and not to publisher}} published a story alleging that Uniqlo had forced employees at its stores and factories in China to work long hours for little pay.  In response, Uniqlo unsuccessfully sued the weekly's publisher, [[Bungeishunj\u016b]], for \u00a5220 million for [[libel]].<ref>Staff (5 June 2011) [http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/nn20110605a9.html \"Uniqlo Takes Bungeishunju to Court for Libel\"]. ''[[The Japan Times]]''. Retrieved 11 July 2013.</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title = Court tosses Uniqlo defamation lawsuit|url = http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2013/10/19/national/crime-legal/court-tosses-uniqlo-defamation-lawsuit/|newspaper = The Japan Times Online|date = 2013-10-19|access-date = 2015-08-28|issn = 0447-5763}}</ref>\n\nA 2015 online video of a couple having sex in a Beijing Uniqlo store changing room became notorious among Chinese internet users. Chinese police arrested at least five people in connection with the incident, allegedly including the couple and three other disseminators of the video, for having 'severely violated socialist core values'.<ref name=\"Chinese police detain suspects linked to viral Uniqlo sex video\">{{cite web|last1=Jiang|first1=Stephen|title=Chinese police detain suspects linked to viral Uniqlo sex video|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2015/07/19/asia/china-uniqlo-sex-video-arrest/|website=[[CNN]]|access-date=22 October 2015}}</ref> The ''[[New York Times]]'' noted that the store's exterior had become a popular venue for people to gather and take pictures in sexual poses reminiscent of the video.<ref name=\"Beijing Police Detain at Least 4 Over Uniqlo Sex Video\">{{cite web|last1=Ramzy|first1=Austin|title=Beijing Police Detain at Least 4 Over Uniqlo Sex Video|url=http://sinosphere.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/07/20/beijing-police-detain-at-least-4-over-uniqlo-sex-video/?_r=0|website=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=22 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Hong Kong SAR ===\n[[File:HK Bus 101 Tour view Des Voeux Road Central Tram body ads Lee Theatre Plaza UNIQLO flagship shop April 2013.JPG|thumb|Uniqlo tram advertising in [[Hong Kong]]]]\nUniqlo has 27 stores in Hong Kong SAR as of May 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.uniqlo.com/hk/shop/|title=\u5e97\u8216\u8cc7\u6599 - UNIQLO|website=www.uniqlo.com|language=zh-TW|access-date=2018-05-22|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===France===\nOn 17 November 2014, Uniqlo opened its first store in Eastern [[France]] (and the second store in France outside [[\u00cele-de-France|Greater Paris]]) in the city of [[Strasbourg, France|Strasbourg]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://france3-regions.francetvinfo.fr/alsace/2014/11/14/uniqlo-ouvre-strasbourg-une-centaine-d-emplois-la-cle-591634.html|title=Uniqlo ouvre \u00e0 Strasbourg, une centaine d'emplois \u00e0 la cl\u00e9 - France 3 Alsace|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Germany===\nTheir German flagship store opened on 11 April 2014 at [[Tauentzienstra\u00dfe]], Berlin.<ref>[http://www.trendjam.de/fashion-mode/erste-deutscher-uniqlo-store-in-berlin-trend-2014-ultra-light-down-jackets-20140628 First German Uniqlo Store] TrendJam Magazine. Retrieved on 2014-04-06</ref> By 2019 the company operated 9 stores in Germany, 6 of those in Berlin.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uniqlo.com/eu/en/content/Stores_Landing_Germany.html|title=UNIQLO Store in Germany|website=www.uniqlo.com|access-date=2019-05-15}}</ref>\n\n=== India ===\nUniqlo has opened a store in [[India]] in Oct 2019, as the company announced on 9 May 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://money.cnn.com/2018/05/09/news/companies/uniqlo-india-store-delhi-japan/index.html?iid=SF_River|title=Uniqlo is entering India's booming retail market|last=Iyengar|first=Rishi|work=CNNMoney|access-date=2018-05-11}}</ref> The company will set up a wholly owned [[subsidiary]] in India.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/life/2018/05/09/uniqlo-owner-targets-12-billion-people-with-first-india-store.html|title=Uniqlo owner targets 1.2 billion people with first India store|last=Post|first=The Jakarta|work=The Jakarta Post|access-date=2018-05-09|language=en}}</ref> It clocked sales of Rs 2.2 crore in the first two days of opening its maiden store in the country. In the coming months, the Japanese retailer plans to open two more outlets in the National Capital Region, one in DLF Avenue Mall in Saket and another smaller version in DLF CyberHub in Gurgaon.\n\n.\n\n===Italy===\nThe first Uniqlo store in Italy was opened in [[Piazza Cordusio]], [[Milan]] on 13 September 2019.\n\n===Malaysia===\nOn 4 November 2010, Uniqlo opened its first store in Malaysia in [[Fahrenheit 88]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uniqlo.com/my/corp/pressrelease/2010/11/countdowntothefirstuniqlostore.html}}</ref><ref>http://www.fastretailing.com/eng/group/news/1007281600.html</ref> located in [[Bukit Bintang]], [[Kuala Lumpur]]. Uniqlo now has 47 outlets located across Malaysia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uniqlo.com/my/shop/}}</ref>\n\n===The Netherlands===\nThe first Dutch Uniqlo store was opened in Amsterdam on 28 September 2018. The official opening was marred by protests against Uniqlo's unethical business practices in their factory in Jakarta, Indonesia.\n\n===The Philippines===\nUniqlo's first store in the Philippines opened at the [[SM Mall of Asia]] on 15 June 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.uniqlo.com/ph/corp/pressrelease/2012/04/uniqlos_first_store_in_philipp.html|title=UNIQLO\u2019s First Store In Philippines To Open In June|last=|first=|date=|website=Uniqlo Philippines|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> On its sixth anniversary, the company opened its flagship store in the country at [[Glorietta|Glorietta 5]] in [[Makati]], it opened on 5 October 2018. The store is the biggest in Southeast Asia.<ref name=\"UniqloSM\">{{Cite news|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/life/10/05/18/in-photos-uniqlo-opens-global-flagship-store-in-manila|title=Uniqlo opens global flagship store in Manila|work=ABS-CBN News|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nUniqlo has 60 stores across the Philippines as of October 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.uniqlo.com/ph/shop|title=Store Locations|website=Uniqlo Philippines}}</ref>\n\nUniqlo has partnered with the [[SM Group]]'s SM Retail Inc. to bring the brand in the Philippines.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/lifestyle/02/09/12/uniqlo-open-first-ph-store-june-sm-moa|title=Uniqlo to open first PH store in June at SM MOA|work=ABS-CBN News|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===Russia===\nOn 2 April 2010, Uniqlo opened its first store in Moscow, Russia. By August 2019 there were 36 Uniqlo outlets in the country, 20 of them in Moscow.<ref>[https://www.uniqlo.com/ru Uniqlo Russia Official site]</ref>\n\n===Singapore===\nOn 9 April 2009, Uniqlo opened its first store at [[Tampines 1]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uniqlo.com/sg/corp/pressrelease/2009/04/uniqlos_first_store_in_singapo.html|title=Uniqlo's first store in Singapore opens to great success|website=www.uniqlo.com|access-date=2017-11-22}}</ref> Its first flagship store in Singapore and Southeast Asia opened 7 years later on 2 September 2016 at [[Orchard Central]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uniqlo.com/sg/corp/pressrelease/2016/03/uniqlo_to_open_first_global_fl.html|title=Uniqlo to Open First Global Flagship Store in Singapore and in Southeast Asia Region|website=www.uniqlo.com|access-date=2017-11-22|df=dmy-all}}</ref> As of 2017, Uniqlo has 25 stores located island wide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uniqlo.com/sg/shop/|title=Store Locator \u2013 Uniqlo|website=www.uniqlo.com|access-date=2017-11-22|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===South Korea===\n[[File:Lotte World Mall Uniqlo 2016.jpg|thumb|right|Uniqlo in [[Lotte World Mall]], [[Seoul]], [[South Korea]]]]\nIn November 2011, Uniqlo generated more than 2 billion won ($1.7 million) in one day's sales on 11 November when it opened Asia's largest flagship store in central [[Seoul]].  The sales figure was the highest ever set by a fashion outlet in Korea. Uniqlo sales over US$1.2 billion with 150 shops in South Korea. Lotte owns 49% of Uniqlo's Korean subdiary.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/national/Detail.jsp?newsMLId=20111117000747|title=Uniqlo posts record daily sales at new flagship store|publisher=Korea Herald|date=2011-11-20 |access-date=2012-12-22|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  It currently operates 180 stores in South Korea.\n\n===Taiwan===\nOn 7 October 2010, Uniqlo opened its first store at [[Hankyu Department Store]]. Uniqlo has 67 store fronts in Taiwan as of June 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uniqlo.com/tw/stores/|script-title=zh:\u5e97\u8217\u8cc7\u8a0a|language=zh|website=www.uniqlo.com/tw/|access-date=2018-06-27|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Thailand===\n[[File:UNIQLOTH.JPG|thumb|right|Uniqlo in [[CentralWorld]], [[Bangkok]], [[Thailand]]]]\nOn 9 September 2011, Uniqlo opened its first store at [[CentralWorld]]. Its largest flagship store in Thailand and Southeast Asia. Uniqlo has 46 store fronts in Thailand as of January 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.uniqlo.com/th/shop/|title=\u0e2a\u0e32\u0e02\u0e32\u0e02\u0e2d\u0e07 UNIQLO|website=www.uniqlo.com/th/|access-date=2018-02-12}}</ref>. Uniqlo newest store in Thailand is at Samyan Mitrtown, opened on 15 November 2019.\n\n===Spain===\nUniqlo began operations in Spain in 2016<ref name=\"elespanol.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.elespanol.com/economia/20160420/118738470_0.html}}</ref> with its on-line store and in September 2017 opened its flagship store in Barcelona<ref name=\"elespanol.com\"/> (Passeig de Gr\u00e0cia). Nowadays, it also owns a second store in Barcelona and one store in Madrid.\n\n===United Kingdom===\nUniqlo currently has 13 shops in England as of 2019. Ambitious expansion plans in the early 2000s were reversed, with 16 shops being closed in 2003,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/money/2003/mar/08/business.japan|title=Uniqlo retreats from British fashion market|date=2003-03-08|publisher=The Guardian|access-date=2016-12-02}}</ref> including those in Manchester,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/business/business-news/uniqlo-to-close-manchester-stores-1141088|title=Uniqlo to close Manchester stores|publisher=Manchester Evening News|date=2004-08-10|access-date=2016-12-02|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Coventry,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thefreelibrary.com/Uniqlo+going+after+just+six+months%3B+STORE+IN+LOWER+PRECINCT+TO+CLOSE...-a099291798 |title=Uniqlo going after just six months; STORE IN LOWER PRECINCT TO CLOSE ALONG WITH 15 OTHERS|access-date=2016-12-02}}</ref> and Leicester. Uniqlo opened a brand new shop in Manchester on Market Street in April 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/whats-on/shopping/hundreds-excited-shoppers-queued-along-16178614}}</ref>\n\n===United States===\n[[File:Uniqlo Chicago.jpg|right|thumb|Uniqlo's flagship store in [[Chicago]] on the [[Magnificent Mile]]]]\n\nIn September 2005, Uniqlo opened the doors to its first United States store in the [[Menlo Park Mall]] located in [[Edison, New Jersey|Edison, NJ]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/10/06/fashion/thursdaystyles/service-with-a-motto-a-japanese-chain-arrives.html?_r=1&oref=slogin|title=Service With a Motto: A Japanese Chain Arrives?|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=6 October 2005}}</ref>  In November 2006, Uniqlo opened its first store in the [[SoHo]] fashion district of [[Manhattan]], [[New York City]]. New fashion designers joined the store's team to boost and rebirth fashion concepts catering to the [[United States|US]] market.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/11/10/business/worldbusiness/10retail.html?_r=1&oref=slogin|title=Basic Chic From Japan. But Will It Sell?|work=The New York Times|date=10 November 2006}}</ref>\n\nAs part of Fast Retailing's 2020 plan the company has stated that it plans to generate $10 billion in annual sales in the United States from 200 stores, which will lead to a location in every major U.S. city. This goal was stated when the company's only U.S. presence was its handful of stores in the New York City area,<ref>{{cite web|last=Wahba|first=Phil|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/10/13/us-fastretailing-idUSTRE79C7IG20111013|title=Reuters|publisher=Reuters|date=2011-10-13|access-date=2014-08-31|df=dmy-all}}</ref> soon after the company began an expansion in the United States.\n\nIn October 2015, Uniqlo opened its first store in the Midwest with a Chicago store on [[Michigan Avenue (Chicago)|Michigan Avenue]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnainfo.com/chicago/20150827/downtown/mag-mile-uniqlo-store-will-be-countrys-2nd-largest|title=Chicago's 1st Uniqlo Store, Opening Oct. 23, Will Be Country's 2nd Largest|publisher=|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151119184234/http://www.dnainfo.com/chicago/20150827/downtown/mag-mile-uniqlo-store-will-be-countrys-2nd-largest|archive-date=19 November 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2019, Uniqlo signed a lease for its first North American distribution center in [[Phillipsburg, NJ]], leasing a space of over 950,000 sq ft. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.globest.com/2019/10/31/japanese-retailer-signs-major-industrial-lease-in-phillipsburg/|title=Japanese Retailer Signs Major Industrial Lease in Phillipsburg|date=31 October 2019|first=John|last=Jordan|website=GlobeSt|language=en|access-date=2020-01-10}}</ref>\n\n===Vietnam===\nUniqlo opened its first store in Ho Chi Minh city in December 2019. The store is located in Parkson Dong Khoi with three floors.\n===Denmark===\nUniqlo opened their first store in Denmark in April 2019. The store is located on [[Str\u00f8get]] in central [[Copenhagen]]. The store includes three storys.\n\n===Sweden===\nThe first Uniqlo store in Sweden opened in August 2018 in Stockholm and covers three storys.\n\n==Controversies==\nIn January 2015, a number of labor rights violations were reported at Uniqlo suppliers in China.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.waronwant.org/media/reality-behind-uniqlos-corporate-social-responsibility-promises|title=The reality behind UNIQLO's corporate social responsibility promises|date=16 June 2015|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://qz.com/324726/your-uniqlo-skinny-jeans-may-have-a-dark-past/|title=Your Uniqlo skinny jeans may have a dark past|first=Lily|last=Kuo|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.corpwatch.org/article.php?id=16018|title=CorpWatch : UNIQLO, Japanese Fast Fashion Label, Accused of Labor Violations|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japantoday.com/category/business/view/uniqlo-under-fire-over-factory-conditions-low-pay-in-china|title=Uniqlo under fire for dealing with Chinese factories accused of putting workers at risk \u2039 Japan Today: Japan News and Discussion|publisher=}}</ref> Uniqlo pledged to remedy the violations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fastretailing.com/eng/csr/news/1501112030.html|title=In Response to Working Condition Claims at UNIQLO Garment and Textile Suppliers in China - FAST RETAILING CO., LTD.|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://fortune.com/2015/01/16/uniqlo-owner-factory-improvements/|title=Uniqlo owner promises to improve working conditions in China|date=16 January 2015|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2015, Uniqlo factory workers went on strike in relation to lay-offs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/china-strike-idUSH9N0YA00A20150616|title=Workers on strike at China factory supplying Uniqlo owner -rights group|date=16 June 2016|publisher=|via=Reuters}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://cleanclothes.org/news/2015/07/24/uniqlo-under-fire-for-factory-closure-after-worker-uprising|title=UNIQLO under fire for factory closure after worker uprising|first=Paul|last=Roeland|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2015, investigations into the measures Uniqlo introduced in the wake of the January 2015 revelations found that Uniqlo's remedies had been only partially successful, with significant violations continuing to occur.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sacom.hk/uniqlorevisit/|title=[Report] [Revised Edition 2016] Unveiling The Labor Rights Violations \u2013 The Second Investigative Report on UNIQLO's Suppliers in China - Sacom|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2015/11/27/business/china-labor-groups-chide-uniqlo-continued-worker-abuses-pollution/|title=China labor groups chide Uniqlo over continued worker abuses, pollution|date=27 November 2015|publisher=|via=Japan Times Online}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2016 the report 'This Way to Dystopia: Exposing UNIQLO's Abuse of Chinese Garment Workers'<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.waronwant.org/resources/way-dystopia-exposing-uniqlo%E2%80%99s-abuse-chinese-garment-workers?_ga=1.221447771.2101001308.1476970212|title=This Way to Dystopia: Exposing UNIQLO's Abuse of Chinese Garment Workers|date=2016-10-19|work=War On Want|access-date=2017-04-01}}</ref> by SACOM and War on Want claimed that it was still the case that \"excessive overtime, low pay, dangerous working conditions and oppressive management\" were common in Uniqlo factories in China and Cambodia.\n \nIn 2019, a number of Australian workers reported that bullying and harassment is rife, there were \"shouting rooms\", and a toxic work culture. They claimed they had to work 18-hour days, had to fold 7 shirts a minute, and everyone leaves with \"some form of PTSD\".<ref>{{cite web |title='Everyone has some form of PTSD': Former Uniqlo employees describe toxic bullying culture |url=https://www.news.com.au/finance/business/retail/everyone-has-some-form-of-ptsd-former-uniqlo-employees-describe-toxic-bullying-culture/news-story/3e355f0f9c64234aa30e95b378735df8|website=news.com.au|access-date=3 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:UNIQLO (4553929855).jpg|thumb|right|Window sign in [[Shinjuku]], 2010.]]\n\n==Notable projects==\n\n; Artist collaborations\n* [[BT21]]\n* [[Takashi Murakami]] \n* [[Kaws]]\n* [[Andy Warhol]]\n* [[Ray Eames|Ray]] and [[Charles Eames]]\n* [[Jean-Michel Basquiat]]\n* [[Keith Haring]]\n* [[Alexander Wang (designer)|Alexander Wang]] \n* [[In\u00e8s de La Fressange]]\n* [[JW Anderson]]\n* Hana Tajima\n* [[Roger Federer]]\n\n=== \"Art for All\" partnership with Jeffrey Deitch ===\nLaunching on 20 January 2017 \"Art for All\" is a partnership with New York art dealer and curator, [[Jeffrey Deitch]]. The project is centered around the sale of 65 limited-edition products made by commissioned artists such as Marie Roberts, [[Starlee Kine]] and Ken Kagami. With a focus on making the collecting of artworks available to a larger audience, the items on sale will all be available for under $100.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessoffashion.com/articles/bof-exclusive/bof-exclusive-uniqlo-partners-with-jeffrey-deitch-on-art-for-all-shop-in-shops|title=BoF Exclusive \u2013 Uniqlo Partners With Jeffrey Deitch on 'Art for All' Shop-in-Shops|last=Sherman|first=Lauren|date=2017-01-12|website=The Business of Fashion|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nThe German fashion designer [[Jil Sander]] joined Uniqlo in 2009, and was appointed [[creative director]] of the brand's menswear and womenswear \u2013 as well as launching a new label, +J collection, which won the 2011 Brit Insurance Design Fashion Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fashion.telegraph.co.uk/news-features/TMG6197136/Jil-Sanders-new-range-for-Uniqlo.html|title=Jil Sander's new range for Uniqlo}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"japansoc\">{{cite web|title=Uniqlo: From Tokyo to New York to Global Brand|url=http://www.japansociety.org/uniqlo_from_tokyo_to_new_york_to_global_brand|date=2007-04-26|first=Katherine|last=Hyde|publisher=Japan Society|access-date=2012-12-22|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Commons category-inline|UNIQLO}}\n\n{{Fast Retailing}}\n\n[[Category:1949 establishments in Japan]]\n[[Category:Clothing brands of Japan]]\n[[Category:Clothing companies of Japan]]\n[[Category:Clothing retailers of Japan]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Yamaguchi Prefecture]]\n[[Category:Fast Retailing]]\n[[Category:Japanese brands]]\n[[Category:Retail companies established in 1949]]\n[[Category:Retail companies based in Tokyo]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies based in Tokyo]]\n[[Category:Shops in Paris]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Japanese casual wear designer, manufacturer and retailer}}\n{{more footnotes|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Uniqlo Co., Ltd.<br>\u682a\u5f0f\u4f1a\u793e\u30e6\u30cb\u30af\u30ed\n| native_name_lang = ja\n| logo = UNIQLO logo.svg\n| logo_caption = Uniqlo logo\n| type = [[subsidiary|Wholly owned subsidiary]]\n| hq_location_country = Japan\n| key_people = [[Tadashi Yanai]] <small>(Chairman, President & CEO)</small><br />Takahiro Wakabayashi <small>(Senior Vice President)</small>\n| industry = [[Fashion]]<br />[[Retail]] \n| products = [[Clothing]]\n| operating_income =\n| net_income =\n| num_employees = 44,424 (2018)\n| parent = [[Fast Retailing]] <br>(2005\u2013present)\n| subsid =\n| homepage = [http://www.uniqlo.com/ uniqlo.com]\n| footnotes =\n| foundation = [[Ube, Yamaguchi|Ube]], [[Yamaguchi Prefecture|Yamaguchi]], [[Japan]]<br>{{start date and age|1949}}\n| location = [[Midtown Tower]], [[Akasaka, Tokyo|Akasaka]]<br>9-chome, [[Minato, Tokyo|Minato]], [[Tokyo]]\n}}\n\n{{Nihongo|'''Uniqlo<!--\"Uniqlo\" lowercase per [[WP:MOSTM]] guide--> Co., Ltd.'''|\u682a\u5f0f\u4f1a\u793e\u30e6\u30cb\u30af\u30ed|Kabushiki-gaisha Yunikuro}} ({{IPAc-en|US|\u02c8|ju\u02d0|n|i|k|l|o\u028a}} {{respell|YOO|nee|kloh}};<ref name=\"japansoc\"/> {{IPA-ja|j\u026f\u0272ik\u026f\u027eo|language}}) is a [[Economy of Japan|Japanese]] [[casual wear]] designer, manufacturer and [[retail]]er.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uniqlo.com/uk/en/company/|title=About Uniqlo {{!}} UNIQLO|website=www.uniqlo.com|language=en|access-date=2018-03-11|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The company is a wholly owned subsidiary of [[Fast Retailing|Fast Retailing Co., Ltd.]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fastretailing.com/eng/group/|title=Group Companies {{!}} FAST RETAILING CO., LTD.|website=www.fastretailing.com|language=en|access-date=2018-03-11|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Uniqlo Shinsaibashisuji Flag ship store Interior view 2014.jpg|thumb|upright|Uniqlo flagship store in Shinsaibashisuji, Osaka]]\n\n===Origins in Japan===\nA Yamaguchi-based company, Ogori Sh\u014dji (which, until then, had been operating men's clothing shops called \"Men's Shop OS\") was founded in March 1949 in [[Ube, Yamaguchi]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fastretailing.com/eng/about/history/|title=1949-2003 {{!}} FAST RETAILING CO., LTD.|website=www.fastretailing.com|language=en|access-date=2018-03-11|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn May 1984, it opened a unisex casual wear store in Fukuro-machi, [[Naka-ku, Hiroshima|Naka-ku]], [[Hiroshima]] under the name \"Unique Clothing Warehouse\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=White|first1=Gillian B.|title=Why Urban Millennials Love Uniqlo|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2019/04/uniqlo-millennials-gap/583219/|website=The Atlantic|access-date=14 March 2019|date=13 March 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Initially, the brand was going to be registered as a shortened contraction of \"unique clothing\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://asia.nikkei.com/Business/Uniqlos-Hong-Kong-role-models-are-failing-the-test-of-time|title=Uniqlo's Hong Kong role models are failing the test of time|last=Kawase|first=Kenji|date=2014-10-23|website=Nikkei Asian Review|language=en-GB|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=2019-05-28|df=dmy-all}}</ref> However, in 1988, during administration work in Hong Kong for registering the brand, staff in charge of registration misread the \"C\" as \"Q\", and that is how the brand name was born.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://toni-marino.com/uniqlo-logo/|title=UNIQLO Logo Designed By Kashiwa Sato|date=2018-07-26|website=Toni Marino|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref> Tadashi Yanai then changed the store name to \"uniqlo\" across Japan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mpfinance.com/htm/finance/20130426/news/ea_eaa3.htm|script-title=ja:\u5beb\u932f\u516c\u53f8\u540d \u5c07\u932f\u5c31\u932f\u4f5c\u54c1\u724c|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151127084446/http://www.mpfinance.com/htm/finance/20130426/news/ea_eaa3.htm|archive-date=27 November 2015|website=mpfinance.com|language=ja|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In September 1991, the name of the company was changed from \"Ogori Sh\u014dji\" to \"Fast Retailing\", and by April 1994, there were over 100 Uniqlo stores operating throughout Japan.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\n===Private-label strategy===\nIn 1997, Fast Retailing adopted a set of strategies from American retailer [[Gap Inc.|The Gap]], known as \"SPA\" (for specialty-store/retailer of private-label apparel), meaning that they would produce their own clothing and sell it exclusively.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}} They engaged the retail brand consultancy, CIA, Inc. / The Brand Architect Group, to guide the company through the realization of this strategy, including consulting on merchandise, visual merchandising and display, store design and a new logo designed by Richard Seireeni and Sy Chen of The Brand Architect Group's Los Angeles office.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}} Uniqlo had begun outsourcing their clothing manufacturing to factories in China where labour was cheap, a well-established corporate practice.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}} Japan was in the depths of a recession at the time, and the low-cost goods proved popular.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theculturetrip.com/asia/japan/articles/a-history-of-uniqlo-in-1-minute/|title=A History Of Uniqlo In 1 Minute|last=Joy|first=Alicia|website=Culture Trip|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref> Their advertising campaigns, clothing quality and new retail layouts also proved fruitful.<ref>{{cite news|last=Nagata|first=Kazuaki|url=http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/nn20091117i1.html|title=Choice, chic, cheap \u2014 no one feels fleeced|work=[[Japan Times]]|page=3|date=2009-11-17|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n{{rquote|right|In creating its clothing lines, Uniqlo embraces both ''shun'' and ''kino-bi''. ''Shun'' [\u65ec] means 'timing, best timing, but also at the same time it's a trend,' something that's updated and just in time, neither early nor late. The company offers clothing basics, but basics that are current, that respond to what's going on today in art and design. ''Kino-bi'' [\u6a5f\u80fd\u7f8e] means function and beauty, joined together: the clothing is presented in an organized, rational manner, and that very organization and rationality creates an artistic pattern and rhythm. All these qualities reflect the defining characteristics of modern Japanese culture, modern '[[Nihonjinron|Japaneseness]].'|Nobuo&nbsp;Domae,&nbsp;CEO, Uniqlo USA (April&nbsp;2007)<ref name=\"japansoc\"/>}}\n\nIn November 1998, they opened their first urban Uniqlo store in [[Tokyo]]'s trendy [[Harajuku]] district, and outlets soon spread to major cities throughout Japan.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}} In 2001, sales turnover and gross profit reached a new peak, with over 500 retail stores in Japan.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}} When Uniqlo decided to expand overseas, it separated Uniqlo from the parent company,<ref name=\"japansoc\"/> and established Fast Retailing (Jiangsu) Apparel Co., Ltd. in China. In 2002 their first Chinese Uniqlo outlet was opened in [[Shanghai]] along with four overseas outlets in [[London]], England.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\n2005 saw more overseas expansion, with stores opening in the United States ([[New York City]]), Hong Kong ([[Tsim Sha Tsui]]) and South Korea ([[Seoul]]), their South Korean expansion being part of a joint venture with [[Lotte (conglomerate)|Lotte]].{{citation needed|date=October 2017}} As of year-end 2005, in addition to its overseas holdings, Uniqlo had around 700 stores within Japan.{{Citation needed|date=September 2009}} By 2006 sales were $4 billion.<ref name=\"japansoc\"/> By April 2007, the company had set a global sales goal of $10 billion and a ranking among the top five global retailers, joining what at the time was [[Gap (clothing retailer)|Gap]], [[H&M]], [[Inditex]], and [[Limited Brands]].<ref name=\"japansoc\"/>\n\nFast Retailing signed a design consulting contract for Uniqlo products with fashion designer [[Jil Sander]] in March 2009.<ref>[http://www.fastretailing.com/eng/about/history/2009.html 2009 | FAST RETAILING CO., LTD]. Fastretailing.com (2010-12-20). Retrieved on 2011-02-16.</ref> [[Shiatzy Chen]] has been approached by Uniqlo to produce a [[capsule collection]] of ready to wear pieces to launch in November 2010 while Asia's largest Uniqlo store outside Japan opened its doors in [[Kuala Lumpur]] in the same month.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\n[[File:Uniqlo jeans.jpg|thumb|Uniqlo jeans at their Tokyo store]]\n\nOn 2 September 2009, Fast Retailing announced that the company would target annual group sales of 5 trillion yen (approx. US$61.2 billion) and pretax profit from operations of 1 trillion yen (approx. US$12.2 billion) by 2020. This means that the company is aiming to become the world's biggest specialty retailer of private label apparel with a continuous growth rate of 20% per year. The figure breaks down as one trillion yen from Uniqlo's Japan business, three trillion yen from its international business, and one trillion yen from {{Clarify span|\"Japan-related and global brand business.\"|date=December 2012}}  The company's international business target breaks down as one trillion yen in China, one trillion in other Asian countries and one trillion in Europe and the United States.<ref>Kensuke Kojima (2011). ''Uniqlo Syndrome''. Toyo Keizai Shinpo Sha. {{ISBN|4-492-76191-8}} Tenkai Japan. ASIN: B004PYDPOK.</ref>\n\nIn October 2018, Uniqlo collaborated with designer [[Alexander Wang (designer)|Alexander Wang]] to create a line of Heattech layerable basics including tank tops, leggings, underwear and bodysuits.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://fashionista.com/2018/10/alexander-wang-uniqlo-heattech-collaboration-collection-prices|title=See Every Piece From the Alexander Wang x Uniqlo Heattech Collaboration|work=Fashionista|access-date=2018-11-16|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==International operations==\n[[File:Uniqlo world map.png|alt=|thumb|300x300px|Map of countries with Uniqlo stores]]\nAs of 30 November 2019, the company reported that 2249 Uniqlo stores were operational worldwide.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fastretailing.com/eng/group/shoplist/|title=Group Outlets {{!}} FAST RETAILING CO., LTD.|last=|first=|date=|website=fastretailing.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref>\n\n===Australia===\n[[File:Uniqlo, Murray Street, Perth, September 2018.jpg|thumb|right|Uniqlo in [[Perth]], [[Australia]]]]\nUniqlo opened its first Australian store in [[Melbourne]] in April 2014.<ref name=\"insideretail-au\"/> In 2015, it expanded into [[Queensland]], with the introduction of two shops in [[Brisbane]].<ref name=\"insideretail-au\">{{cite web|url=https://www.insideretail.com.au/blog/2015/09/01/uniqlo-to-launch-in-queensland/|title=Uniqlo heads to Queensland|date=1 September 2015|publisher=}}</ref> Uniqlo opened a shop in [[Chadstone Shopping Centre]] in [[Melbourne]], Victoria, the largest shopping centre in the southern hemisphere, in October 2016 when it was redeveloped.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uniqlo.com/au/shop/chadstone.html |title=Uniqlo Chadstone}}</ref> There are currently 22 stores in Australia, including in [[Sydney]] and [[Perth]]. There is also a Uniqlo store in the Eastland Shopping Centre in [[Ringwood]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uniqlo.com/au/shop/ |title=STORE LOCATOR - UNIQLO}}</ref>\n\n===Bangladesh===\nUniqlo started their first store at the [[New Elephant road]] in [[Dhaka]], [[Bangladesh]], on 5 July 2013. Uniqlo is known as Grameen Uniqlo there due to their social business concept JV with [[Grameen Bank]]. There are currently 15 stores in Dhaka, 1 store in [[Gazipur]] and 1 in [[Narsingdi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.grameenuniqlo.com/store-locator|title=Stores|date=19 July 2019|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Belgium===\nThe first Belgian Uniqlo store opened in October 2015 at [[Meir, Antwerp]].<ref>[http://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20170518_02887897 Uniqlo opent eerste winkel in hartje Brussel. De Standaard. 18/05/2017 at 10:34 by edm.]</ref> A second store followed suit at the [[Wijnegem Shopping Center]] on 25 March in the same year.<ref>[https://www.nieuwsblad.be/cnt/dmf20160308_02170904 Uniqlo opent op 25 maart in Wijnegem Shopping Center. Nieuwsblad. 08/03/2016 at 11:41 by inke.]</ref> 19 October 2017 saw the opening of a third store in [[Brussels]].<ref>Tine Stoop [http://marieclaire.be/nl/uniqlo-brussel-opening/ Uniqlo opent derde Belgische vestiging in Brussel] Marie Claire, 19 October 2017</ref>\n\n===Canada===\n[[File:UNIQLOEatonCenter.jpg|thumb|Uniqlo in Canada]]\nUniqlo opened their first Canadian store at the [[Toronto Eaton Centre]] on 30 September 2016, followed by a second store at the [[Yorkdale Shopping Centre]] on 20 October 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/life/2016/09/29/uniqlo-set-to-launch-first-canadian-store-at-the-eaton-centre.html| title=Uniqlo set to launch first Canadian store at the Eaton Centre|first=Leanne|last=Delap|date=2016-09-29|publisher=[[Toronto Star]]|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Measuring at 28,000 and 24,000 square feet, both stores are five times the size of the [[Muji]] store that opened in Toronto in 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/business/2016/06/19/uniqlo-targets-a-unique-apparel-market-everyone.html|title=Uniqlo targets a unique apparel market: Everyone|first=Francine|last=Kopun|date=2016-06-19|publisher=Toronto Star|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Three new stores in Ontario opened in 2018 at [[Vaughan Mills]], [[CF Markville]] and [[Square One Shopping Centre]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://dailyhive.com/toronto/toronto-uniqlo-announces-gta-opening-dates-2018|title=UNIQLO officially announces opening dates of its new GTA locations|last=Staff|first=DH Toronto|date=2018-08-29|work=Daily Hive|access-date=2018-10-26|language=en|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Uniqlo opened the new Oshawa location at the [[Oshawa Centre]] in March 2019 and opened the new Newmarket location at the [[Upper Canada Mall]] in April 2019, bringing the total number of stores in Ontario to seven.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.retail-insider.com/retail-insider/2019/1/uniqlo-ramps-up-canadian-expansion-with-2-store-announcements|title=Uniqlo Ramps Up Canadian Expansion with 2 Store Announcements|website=Retail Insider|language=en-CA|access-date=2019-01-22|df=dmy-all}}</ref> A third Canadian store, the first outside of Ontario and the first in Western Canada, opened at [[Burnaby]]'s [[Metropolis at Metrotown]] in October 2017 <ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.straight.com/life/977376/photos-uniqlo-finally-lands-west-coast-third-canadian-location| title=Photos: Uniqlo finally lands on West Coast with third Canadian location|first=Lucy|last=Lau|date=5 October 2017|publisher=[[The Georgia Straight]]}}</ref> to be followed by Surrey's [[Guildford Town Centre (mall)|Guildford Town Centre]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.guildfordtowncentre.com/stores/unisex-apparel-3/uniqlo-coming-soon/}}</ref> and [[Richmond Centre (mall)|Richmond Centre]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.richmond-news.com/news/uniqlo-coming-to-richmond-centre-1.23153895}}</ref> in Richmond, BC. A new store opened at [[Coquitlam Centre]] in Coquitlam, BC on 14 September 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straight.com/life/1126316/uniqlos-coquitlam-centre-location-opens-september-14|title=Uniqlo's Coquitlam Centre location opens on September 14|last=Lau|first=Lucy|date=2018-08-29|website=The Georgia Straight|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=2019-06-26|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://biv.com/article/2018/08/uniqlo-open-fourth-bc-store-coquitlam-centre|title=Uniqlo to open fourth B.C. store at Coquitlam Centre|last=Korstrom|first=Glen|date=|website=Business in Vancouver|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=2019-06-26|df=dmy-all}}</ref> A new [[West Edmonton Mall]] store opened on 27 September 2019.<ref>https://www.uniqlo.com/ca/en/information/press-release/2019/0604</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://edmonton.ctvnews.ca/this-popular-retailer-to-set-up-shop-in-west-edmonton-mall-1.4463528|title=This popular retailer to set up shop in West Edmonton Mall|last=|first=|date=2019-06-12|website=CTV News Edmonton|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=2019-06-26|df=dmy-all}}</ref> A new location is set to open at the [[Montreal Eaton Centre|Eaton Centre]] in Montreal in late 2020.\n\n===China===\n[[File:BJ Tour Beijing \u5317\u4eac \u4e09\u91cc\u5c6f Sanlitun Village shop UNIQLO mall facade visitors trees Aug-2010.JPG|thumb|right|Uniqlo in [[Sanlitun]], [[Beijing]], [[China]]]]\nUniqlo entered the [[Chinese mainland]] market in 2002. {{as of|August 2017}}, there were 555 stores in China, including in [[Beijing]], [[Guangzhou]], [[Chongqing]], [[Chengdu]], Nanjing, Ningbo, Shanghai, Shenzhen, Shijia, Tianjin and Xi'an.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fastretailing.com/eng/group/strategy/china.html|title=China - FAST RETAILING CO LTD|website=www.fastretailing.com}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2011, the magazine [[Bungeishunj\u016b|''Shukan Bunshun'']]{{clarify|date=July 2013|reason=is this same publication as \"Bungeishunj\u016b (magazine)\"?  if so, should link to wiki article on magazine and not to publisher}} published a story alleging that Uniqlo had forced employees at its stores and factories in China to work long hours for little pay.  In response, Uniqlo unsuccessfully sued the weekly's publisher, [[Bungeishunj\u016b]], for \u00a5220 million for [[libel]].<ref>Staff (5 June 2011) [http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/nn20110605a9.html \"Uniqlo Takes Bungeishunju to Court for Libel\"]. ''[[The Japan Times]]''. Retrieved 11 July 2013.</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title = Court tosses Uniqlo defamation lawsuit|url = http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2013/10/19/national/crime-legal/court-tosses-uniqlo-defamation-lawsuit/|newspaper = The Japan Times Online|date = 2013-10-19|access-date = 2015-08-28|issn = 0447-5763}}</ref>\n\nA 2015 online video of a couple having sex in a Beijing Uniqlo store changing room became notorious among Chinese internet users. Chinese police arrested at least five people in connection with the incident, allegedly including the couple and three other disseminators of the video, for having 'severely violated socialist core values'.<ref name=\"Chinese police detain suspects linked to viral Uniqlo sex video\">{{cite web|last1=Jiang|first1=Stephen|title=Chinese police detain suspects linked to viral Uniqlo sex video|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2015/07/19/asia/china-uniqlo-sex-video-arrest/|website=[[CNN]]|access-date=22 October 2015}}</ref> The ''[[New York Times]]'' noted that the store's exterior had become a popular venue for people to gather and take pictures in sexual poses reminiscent of the video.<ref name=\"Beijing Police Detain at Least 4 Over Uniqlo Sex Video\">{{cite web|last1=Ramzy|first1=Austin|title=Beijing Police Detain at Least 4 Over Uniqlo Sex Video|url=http://sinosphere.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/07/20/beijing-police-detain-at-least-4-over-uniqlo-sex-video/?_r=0|website=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=22 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Hong Kong SAR ===\n[[File:HK Bus 101 Tour view Des Voeux Road Central Tram body ads Lee Theatre Plaza UNIQLO flagship shop April 2013.JPG|thumb|Uniqlo tram advertising in [[Hong Kong]]]]\nUniqlo has 27 stores in Hong Kong SAR as of May 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.uniqlo.com/hk/shop/|title=\u5e97\u8216\u8cc7\u6599 - UNIQLO|website=www.uniqlo.com|language=zh-TW|access-date=2018-05-22|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===France===\nOn 17 November 2014, Uniqlo opened its first store in Eastern [[France]] (and the second store in France outside [[\u00cele-de-France|Greater Paris]]) in the city of [[Strasbourg, France|Strasbourg]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://france3-regions.francetvinfo.fr/alsace/2014/11/14/uniqlo-ouvre-strasbourg-une-centaine-d-emplois-la-cle-591634.html|title=Uniqlo ouvre \u00e0 Strasbourg, une centaine d'emplois \u00e0 la cl\u00e9 - France 3 Alsace|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Germany===\nTheir German flagship store opened on 11 April 2014 at [[Tauentzienstra\u00dfe]], Berlin.<ref>[http://www.trendjam.de/fashion-mode/erste-deutscher-uniqlo-store-in-berlin-trend-2014-ultra-light-down-jackets-20140628 First German Uniqlo Store] TrendJam Magazine. Retrieved on 2014-04-06</ref> By 2019 the company operated 9 stores in Germany, 6 of those in Berlin.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uniqlo.com/eu/en/content/Stores_Landing_Germany.html|title=UNIQLO Store in Germany|website=www.uniqlo.com|access-date=2019-05-15}}</ref>\n\n=== India ===\nUniqlo has opened a store in [[India]] in Oct 2019, as the company announced on 9 May 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://money.cnn.com/2018/05/09/news/companies/uniqlo-india-store-delhi-japan/index.html?iid=SF_River|title=Uniqlo is entering India's booming retail market|last=Iyengar|first=Rishi|work=CNNMoney|access-date=2018-05-11}}</ref> The company will set up a wholly owned [[subsidiary]] in India.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/life/2018/05/09/uniqlo-owner-targets-12-billion-people-with-first-india-store.html|title=Uniqlo owner targets 1.2 billion people with first India store|last=Post|first=The Jakarta|work=The Jakarta Post|access-date=2018-05-09|language=en}}</ref> It clocked sales of Rs 2.2 crore in the first two days of opening its maiden store in the country. In the coming months, the Japanese retailer plans to open two more outlets in the National Capital Region, one in DLF Avenue Mall in Saket and another smaller version in DLF CyberHub in Gurgaon.\n\n.\n\n===Italy===\nThe first Uniqlo store in Italy was opened in [[Piazza Cordusio]], [[Milan]] on 13 September 2019.\n\n===Malaysia===\nOn 4 November 2010, Uniqlo opened its first store in Malaysia in [[Fahrenheit 88]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uniqlo.com/my/corp/pressrelease/2010/11/countdowntothefirstuniqlostore.html}}</ref><ref>http://www.fastretailing.com/eng/group/news/1007281600.html</ref> located in [[Bukit Bintang]], [[Kuala Lumpur]]. Uniqlo now has 47 outlets located across Malaysia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uniqlo.com/my/shop/}}</ref>\n\n===The Netherlands===\nThe first Dutch Uniqlo store was opened in Amsterdam on 28 September 2018. The official opening was marred by protests against Uniqlo's unethical business practices in their factory in Jakarta, Indonesia.\n\n===The Philippines===\nUniqlo's first store in the Philippines opened at the [[SM Mall of Asia]] on 15 June 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.uniqlo.com/ph/corp/pressrelease/2012/04/uniqlos_first_store_in_philipp.html|title=UNIQLO\u2019s First Store In Philippines To Open In June|last=|first=|date=|website=Uniqlo Philippines|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> On its sixth anniversary, the company opened its flagship store in the country at [[Glorietta|Glorietta 5]] in [[Makati]], it opened on 5 October 2018. The store is the biggest in Southeast Asia.<ref name=\"UniqloSM\">{{Cite news|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/life/10/05/18/in-photos-uniqlo-opens-global-flagship-store-in-manila|title=Uniqlo opens global flagship store in Manila|work=ABS-CBN News|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nUniqlo has 60 stores across the Philippines as of October 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.uniqlo.com/ph/shop|title=Store Locations|website=Uniqlo Philippines}}</ref>\n\nUniqlo has partnered with the [[SM Group]]'s SM Retail Inc. to bring the brand in the Philippines.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/lifestyle/02/09/12/uniqlo-open-first-ph-store-june-sm-moa|title=Uniqlo to open first PH store in June at SM MOA|work=ABS-CBN News|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===Russia===\nOn 2 April 2010, Uniqlo opened its first store in Moscow, Russia. By August 2019 there were 36 Uniqlo outlets in the country, 20 of them in Moscow.<ref>[https://www.uniqlo.com/ru Uniqlo Russia Official site]</ref>\n\n===Singapore===\nOn 9 April 2009, Uniqlo opened its first store at [[Tampines 1]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uniqlo.com/sg/corp/pressrelease/2009/04/uniqlos_first_store_in_singapo.html|title=Uniqlo's first store in Singapore opens to great success|website=www.uniqlo.com|access-date=2017-11-22}}</ref> Its first flagship store in Singapore and Southeast Asia opened 7 years later on 2 September 2016 at [[Orchard Central]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uniqlo.com/sg/corp/pressrelease/2016/03/uniqlo_to_open_first_global_fl.html|title=Uniqlo to Open First Global Flagship Store in Singapore and in Southeast Asia Region|website=www.uniqlo.com|access-date=2017-11-22|df=dmy-all}}</ref> As of 2017, Uniqlo has 25 stores located island wide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uniqlo.com/sg/shop/|title=Store Locator \u2013 Uniqlo|website=www.uniqlo.com|access-date=2017-11-22|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===South Korea===\n[[File:Lotte World Mall Uniqlo 2016.jpg|thumb|right|Uniqlo in [[Lotte World Mall]], [[Seoul]], [[South Korea]]]]\nIn November 2011, Uniqlo generated more than 2 billion won ($1.7 million) in one day's sales on 11 November when it opened Asia's largest flagship store in central [[Seoul]].  The sales figure was the highest ever set by a fashion outlet in Korea. Uniqlo sales over US$1.2 billion with 150 shops in South Korea. Lotte owns 49% of Uniqlo's Korean subdiary.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/national/Detail.jsp?newsMLId=20111117000747|title=Uniqlo posts record daily sales at new flagship store|publisher=Korea Herald|date=2011-11-20 |access-date=2012-12-22|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  It currently operates 180 stores in South Korea.\n\n===Taiwan===\nOn 7 October 2010, Uniqlo opened its first store at [[Hankyu Department Store]]. Uniqlo has 67 store fronts in Taiwan as of June 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uniqlo.com/tw/stores/|script-title=zh:\u5e97\u8217\u8cc7\u8a0a|language=zh|website=www.uniqlo.com/tw/|access-date=2018-06-27|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Thailand===\n[[File:UNIQLOTH.JPG|thumb|right|Uniqlo in [[CentralWorld]], [[Bangkok]], [[Thailand]]]]\nOn 9 September 2011, Uniqlo opened its first store at [[CentralWorld]]. Its largest flagship store in Thailand and Southeast Asia. Uniqlo has 46 store fronts in Thailand as of January 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.uniqlo.com/th/shop/|title=\u0e2a\u0e32\u0e02\u0e32\u0e02\u0e2d\u0e07 UNIQLO|website=www.uniqlo.com/th/|access-date=2018-02-12}}</ref>. Uniqlo newest store in Thailand is at Samyan Mitrtown, opened on 15 November 2019.\n\n===Spain===\nUniqlo began operations in Spain in 2016<ref name=\"elespanol.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.elespanol.com/economia/20160420/118738470_0.html}}</ref> with its on-line store and in September 2017 opened its flagship store in Barcelona<ref name=\"elespanol.com\"/> (Passeig de Gr\u00e0cia). Nowadays, it also owns a second store in Barcelona and one store in Madrid.\n\n===United Kingdom===\nUniqlo currently has 13 shops in England as of 2019. Ambitious expansion plans in the early 2000s were reversed, with 16 shops being closed in 2003,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/money/2003/mar/08/business.japan|title=Uniqlo retreats from British fashion market|date=2003-03-08|publisher=The Guardian|access-date=2016-12-02}}</ref> including those in Manchester,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/business/business-news/uniqlo-to-close-manchester-stores-1141088|title=Uniqlo to close Manchester stores|publisher=Manchester Evening News|date=2004-08-10|access-date=2016-12-02|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Coventry,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thefreelibrary.com/Uniqlo+going+after+just+six+months%3B+STORE+IN+LOWER+PRECINCT+TO+CLOSE...-a099291798 |title=Uniqlo going after just six months; STORE IN LOWER PRECINCT TO CLOSE ALONG WITH 15 OTHERS|access-date=2016-12-02}}</ref> and Leicester. Uniqlo opened a brand new shop in Manchester on Market Street in April 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/whats-on/shopping/hundreds-excited-shoppers-queued-along-16178614}}</ref>\n\n===United States===\n[[File:Uniqlo Chicago.jpg|right|thumb|Uniqlo's flagship store in [[Chicago]] on the [[Magnificent Mile]]]]\n\nIn September 2005, Uniqlo opened the doors to its first United States store in the [[Menlo Park Mall]] located in [[Edison, New Jersey|Edison, NJ]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/10/06/fashion/thursdaystyles/service-with-a-motto-a-japanese-chain-arrives.html?_r=1&oref=slogin|title=Service With a Motto: A Japanese Chain Arrives?|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=6 October 2005}}</ref>  In November 2006, Uniqlo opened its first store in the [[SoHo]] fashion district of [[Manhattan]], [[New York City]]. New fashion designers joined the store's team to boost and rebirth fashion concepts catering to the [[United States|US]] market.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/11/10/business/worldbusiness/10retail.html?_r=1&oref=slogin|title=Basic Chic From Japan. But Will It Sell?|work=The New York Times|date=10 November 2006}}</ref>\n\nAs part of Fast Retailing's 2020 plan the company has stated that it plans to generate $10 billion in annual sales in the United States from 200 stores, which will lead to a location in every major U.S. city. This goal was stated when the company's only U.S. presence was its handful of stores in the New York City area,<ref>{{cite web|last=Wahba|first=Phil|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/10/13/us-fastretailing-idUSTRE79C7IG20111013|title=Reuters|publisher=Reuters|date=2011-10-13|access-date=2014-08-31|df=dmy-all}}</ref> soon after the company began an expansion in the United States.\n\nIn October 2015, Uniqlo opened its first store in the Midwest with a Chicago store on [[Michigan Avenue (Chicago)|Michigan Avenue]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnainfo.com/chicago/20150827/downtown/mag-mile-uniqlo-store-will-be-countrys-2nd-largest|title=Chicago's 1st Uniqlo Store, Opening Oct. 23, Will Be Country's 2nd Largest|publisher=|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151119184234/http://www.dnainfo.com/chicago/20150827/downtown/mag-mile-uniqlo-store-will-be-countrys-2nd-largest|archive-date=19 November 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2019, Uniqlo signed a lease for its first North American distribution center in [[Phillipsburg, NJ]], leasing a space of over 950,000 sq ft. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.globest.com/2019/10/31/japanese-retailer-signs-major-industrial-lease-in-phillipsburg/|title=Japanese Retailer Signs Major Industrial Lease in Phillipsburg|date=31 October 2019|first=John|last=Jordan|website=GlobeSt|language=en|access-date=2020-01-10}}</ref>\n\n===Vietnam===\nUniqlo opened its first store in Ho Chi Minh city in December 2019. The store is located in Parkson Dong Khoi with three floors.\n===Denmark===\nUniqlo opened their first store in Denmark in April 2019. The store is located on [[Str\u00f8get]] in central [[Copenhagen]]. The store includes three storys.\n\n===Sweden===\nThe first Uniqlo store in Sweden opened in August 2018 in Stockholm and covers three storys.\n\n==Controversies==\nIn January 2015, a number of labor rights violations were reported at Uniqlo suppliers in China.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.waronwant.org/media/reality-behind-uniqlos-corporate-social-responsibility-promises|title=The reality behind UNIQLO's corporate social responsibility promises|date=16 June 2015|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://qz.com/324726/your-uniqlo-skinny-jeans-may-have-a-dark-past/|title=Your Uniqlo skinny jeans may have a dark past|first=Lily|last=Kuo|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.corpwatch.org/article.php?id=16018|title=CorpWatch : UNIQLO, Japanese Fast Fashion Label, Accused of Labor Violations|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japantoday.com/category/business/view/uniqlo-under-fire-over-factory-conditions-low-pay-in-china|title=Uniqlo under fire for dealing with Chinese factories accused of putting workers at risk \u2039 Japan Today: Japan News and Discussion|publisher=}}</ref> Uniqlo pledged to remedy the violations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fastretailing.com/eng/csr/news/1501112030.html|title=In Response to Working Condition Claims at UNIQLO Garment and Textile Suppliers in China - FAST RETAILING CO., LTD.|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://fortune.com/2015/01/16/uniqlo-owner-factory-improvements/|title=Uniqlo owner promises to improve working conditions in China|date=16 January 2015|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2015, Uniqlo factory workers went on strike in relation to lay-offs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/china-strike-idUSH9N0YA00A20150616|title=Workers on strike at China factory supplying Uniqlo owner -rights group|date=16 June 2016|publisher=|via=Reuters}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://cleanclothes.org/news/2015/07/24/uniqlo-under-fire-for-factory-closure-after-worker-uprising|title=UNIQLO under fire for factory closure after worker uprising|first=Paul|last=Roeland|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2015, investigations into the measures Uniqlo introduced in the wake of the January 2015 revelations found that Uniqlo's remedies had been only partially successful, with significant violations continuing to occur.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sacom.hk/uniqlorevisit/|title=[Report] [Revised Edition 2016] Unveiling The Labor Rights Violations \u2013 The Second Investigative Report on UNIQLO's Suppliers in China - Sacom|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2015/11/27/business/china-labor-groups-chide-uniqlo-continued-worker-abuses-pollution/|title=China labor groups chide Uniqlo over continued worker abuses, pollution|date=27 November 2015|publisher=|via=Japan Times Online}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2016 the report 'This Way to Dystopia: Exposing UNIQLO's Abuse of Chinese Garment Workers'<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.waronwant.org/resources/way-dystopia-exposing-uniqlo%E2%80%99s-abuse-chinese-garment-workers?_ga=1.221447771.2101001308.1476970212|title=This Way to Dystopia: Exposing UNIQLO's Abuse of Chinese Garment Workers|date=2016-10-19|work=War On Want|access-date=2017-04-01}}</ref> by SACOM and War on Want claimed that it was still the case that \"excessive overtime, low pay, dangerous working conditions and oppressive management\" were common in Uniqlo factories in China and Cambodia.\n \nIn 2019, a number of Australian workers reported that bullying and harassment is rife, there were \"shouting rooms\", and a toxic work culture. They claimed they had to work 18-hour days, had to fold 7 shirts a minute, and everyone leaves with \"some form of PTSD\".<ref>{{cite web |title='Everyone has some form of PTSD': Former Uniqlo employees describe toxic bullying culture |url=https://www.news.com.au/finance/business/retail/everyone-has-some-form-of-ptsd-former-uniqlo-employees-describe-toxic-bullying-culture/news-story/3e355f0f9c64234aa30e95b378735df8|website=news.com.au|access-date=3 March 2019}}</ref> Also, former HR manager Melanie Bell is suing UNIQLO for $1 million, claiming that she had been bullied and discriminated against due to her \"caucasian heritage\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Uniqlo execs named in $1 million bullying legal claim 'discriminated against caucasian manager'|url=https://www.news.com.au/finance/work/at-work/uniqlo-execs-named-in-1-million-bullying-legal-claim-discriminated-against-caucasian-manager/news-story/d1769035f40522a38698aff4138b1047|website=news.com.au|access-date=3 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:UNIQLO (4553929855).jpg|thumb|right|Window sign in [[Shinjuku]], 2010.]]\n\n==Notable projects==\n\n; Artist collaborations\n* [[BT21]]\n* [[Takashi Murakami]] \n* [[Kaws]]\n* [[Andy Warhol]]\n* [[Ray Eames|Ray]] and [[Charles Eames]]\n* [[Jean-Michel Basquiat]]\n* [[Keith Haring]]\n* [[Alexander Wang (designer)|Alexander Wang]] \n* [[In\u00e8s de La Fressange]]\n* [[JW Anderson]]\n* Hana Tajima\n* [[Roger Federer]]\n\n=== \"Art for All\" partnership with Jeffrey Deitch ===\nLaunching on 20 January 2017 \"Art for All\" is a partnership with New York art dealer and curator, [[Jeffrey Deitch]]. The project is centered around the sale of 65 limited-edition products made by commissioned artists such as Marie Roberts, [[Starlee Kine]] and Ken Kagami. With a focus on making the collecting of artworks available to a larger audience, the items on sale will all be available for under $100.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessoffashion.com/articles/bof-exclusive/bof-exclusive-uniqlo-partners-with-jeffrey-deitch-on-art-for-all-shop-in-shops|title=BoF Exclusive \u2013 Uniqlo Partners With Jeffrey Deitch on 'Art for All' Shop-in-Shops|last=Sherman|first=Lauren|date=2017-01-12|website=The Business of Fashion|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nThe German fashion designer [[Jil Sander]] joined Uniqlo in 2009, and was appointed [[creative director]] of the brand's menswear and womenswear \u2013 as well as launching a new label, +J collection, which won the 2011 Brit Insurance Design Fashion Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fashion.telegraph.co.uk/news-features/TMG6197136/Jil-Sanders-new-range-for-Uniqlo.html|title=Jil Sander's new range for Uniqlo}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"japansoc\">{{cite web|title=Uniqlo: From Tokyo to New York to Global Brand|url=http://www.japansociety.org/uniqlo_from_tokyo_to_new_york_to_global_brand|date=2007-04-26|first=Katherine|last=Hyde|publisher=Japan Society|access-date=2012-12-22|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Commons category-inline|UNIQLO}}\n\n{{Fast Retailing}}\n\n[[Category:1949 establishments in Japan]]\n[[Category:Clothing brands of Japan]]\n[[Category:Clothing companies of Japan]]\n[[Category:Clothing retailers of Japan]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Yamaguchi Prefecture]]\n[[Category:Fast Retailing]]\n[[Category:Japanese brands]]\n[[Category:Retail companies established in 1949]]\n[[Category:Retail companies based in Tokyo]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies based in Tokyo]]\n[[Category:Shops in Paris]]\n", "name_user": "Sterrekong", "label": "safe", "comment": "Settled in favor of uniqlo , false accusation.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Uniqlo"}
{"title_page": "Fioletovo", "text_new": "{{coord|40|43|29|N|44|42|50|E|display=title}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name =Fioletovo\n|native_name =\n|image_skyline =Fioletovo1_(6_sept_2008).jpg\n|imagesize =\n|pushpin_map            =Armenia\n|mapsize                =150px\n|subdivision_type       =Country\n|subdivision_name       =[[Armenia]]\n|subdivision_type1      =[[Administrative divisions of Armenia|Marz (Province)]]\n|subdivision_name1      =[[Lori Province]]\n|leader_title           = \n|leader_name            = \n|established_title      =\n|established_date       = \n|area_total_km2           = \n|area_footnotes           = \n|population_as_of         = 2008\n|population_total =1373\n|population_density_km2   =\n|timezone =&nbsp;\n|utc_offset             = +4\n|timezone_DST           = \n|utc_offset_DST         = \n|coordinates            = {{coord|40|43|29|N|44|42|50|E|region:AM|display=inline}}\n|elevation_m            = 1670\n|area_code              = \n|website                = \n}}\n'''Fioletovo''' ({{lang-hy|\u0556\u056b\u0578\u056c\u0565\u057f\u0578\u057e\u0578}}) is a village in the [[Lori Province]] of [[Armenia]]. It was known as '''Nikitino''' until 1936, when it was renamed Fioletovo in honour of the [[Russian people|Russian]] [[Communism|Communist]] activist and one of the [[26 Baku Commissars]] [[Ivan Fioletov]].<ref>[http://www.cadastre.am/storage/files/pages/pg_907871769_HH_bnak._bar..pdf Municipalities of Armenia]</ref>\n\nIn the 1840s the villages was settled by [[Spiritual Christianity|Spiritual Christians]] relocated from Russia. Today it is inhabited by 3 congregation of' ''Dukhovne Kristiane Molokane (Spiritual Christians Molokan)''\n and one congregation of ''Postoyane Kristiane Molokane (Constant Christian Molokans)''.\n\nThe village has an extremely cold winter with a cool and mild summer. It lies under a thick layer of snow during the long winter season, where only the roofs of houses could be seen from the top with their smoking chimneys. The population of the village is diminishing year by year as the emigration is growing among its residents, who are trying to look for better economical conditions, either in Armenia or abroad.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Fioletovo2 (6 sept 2008).jpg|Fioletovo\nFile:Fioletovo5 (6 sept 2008).jpg|A villager in Fioletovo\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Lori}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Lori Province]]\n[[Category:Erivan Governorate]]\n\n{{Lori-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{coord|40|43|29|N|44|42|50|E|display=title}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name =Fioletovo\n|native_name =\n|image_skyline =Fioletovo1_(6_sept_2008).jpg\n|imagesize =\n|pushpin_map            =Armenia\n|mapsize                =150px\n|subdivision_type       =Country\n|subdivision_name       =[[Armenia]]\n|subdivision_type1      =[[Administrative divisions of Armenia|Marz (Province)]]\n|subdivision_name1      =[[Lori Province]]\n|leader_title           = \n|leader_name            = \n|established_title      =\n|established_date       = \n|area_total_km2           = \n|area_footnotes           = \n|population_as_of         = 2008\n|population_total =1373\n|population_density_km2   =\n|timezone =&nbsp;\n|utc_offset             = +4\n|timezone_DST           = \n|utc_offset_DST         = \n|coordinates            = {{coord|40|43|29|N|44|42|50|E|region:AM|display=inline}}\n|elevation_m            = 1670\n|area_code              = \n|website                = \n}}\n'''Fioletovo''' ({{lang-hy|\u0556\u056b\u0578\u056c\u0565\u057f\u0578\u057e\u0578}}) is a village in the [[Lori Province]] of [[Armenia]]. It was known as '''Nikitino''' until 1936, when it was renamed Fioletovo in honour of the [[Russian people|Russian]] [[Communism|Communist]] activist and one of the [[26 Baku Commissars]] [[Ivan Fioletov]].<ref>[http://www.cadastre.am/storage/files/pages/pg_907871769_HH_bnak._bar..pdf Municipalities of Armenia]</ref>\n\nIn the 1840s the villages was settled by [[Spiritual Christianity|Spiritual Christians]] relocated from Russia. Today it is inhabited by 3 congregation of ''[http://www.molokane.org/taxonomy Dukh-i-zhizniki]'' and one congregation of ''[[Molokans|Molokane]]''.\n\nThe village has an extremely cold winter with a cool and mild summer. It lies under a thick layer of snow during the long winter season, where only the roofs of houses could be seen from the top with their smoking chimneys. The population of the village is diminishing year by year as the emigration is growing among its residents, who are trying to look for better economical conditions, either in Armenia or abroad.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Fioletovo2 (6 sept 2008).jpg|Fioletovo\nFile:Fioletovo5 (6 sept 2008).jpg|A villager in Fioletovo\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Lori}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Lori Province]]\n[[Category:Erivan Governorate]]\n\n{{Lori-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Living fountain", "label": "safe", "comment": "Naming corrections", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fioletovo"}
