h]] || 1956\u20131962, 1964\u20131965\n|-\n|| Hon [[Jack Renshaw]] || Labor || [[Electoral district of Castlereagh|Castlereagh]] || 1941\u20131980\n|-\n|| [[Bill Rigby (politician)|Bill Rigby]] || Labor || [[Electoral district of Hurstville|Hurstville]] || 1959\u20131965\n|-\n|| [[Ian Robinson (Australian politician)|Ian Robinson]] || Country || [[Electoral district of Casino|Casino]] || 1953\u20131963\n|-\n|| [[Jim Robson (politician)|Jim Robson]] || Labor || [[Electoral district of Hartley (New South Wales)|Hartley]] || 1956\u20131965\n|-\n|| Hon [[Norm Ryan]] || Labor || [[Electoral district of Marrickville|Marrickville]] || 1953\u20131973\n|-\n|| [[Thomas Ryan (New South Wales politician)|Thomas Ryan]] || Labor || [[Electoral district of Auburn|Auburn]] || 1956\u20131965\n|-\n|| [[John Seiffert]] || Labor || [[Electoral district of Monaro|Monaro]] || 1941\u20131965\n|-\n|| Hon [[Bill Sheahan (politician)|Bill Sheahan]] || Labor || [[Electoral district of Burrinjuck|Burrinjuck]] || 1941\u20131973\n|-\n|| [[Jim Simpson (Australian politician)|Jim Simpson]] || Labor || [[Electoral district of Lake Macquarie|Lake Macquarie]] || 1950\u20131968\n|-\n|| [[Albert Sloss]] || Labor || [[Electoral district of King (New South Wales)|King]] || 1956\u20131973\n|-\n|| [[Stanley Stephens (Australian politician)|Stanley Stephens]] || Country || [[Electoral district of Byron|Byron]] || 1944\u20131973\n|-\n|| [[Jack Stewart (New South Wales politician)|Jack Stewart]] || Labor || [[Electoral district of Kahibah|Kahibah]] || 1957\u20131972\n|-\n|| [[Sydney Storey]] || Liberal || [[Electoral district of Hornsby|Hornsby]] || 1941\u20131962\n|-\n|| [[Jim Taylor (politician)|Jim Taylor]] {{ref label|5|5|5}} || Country || [[Electoral district of Temora|Temora]] || 1960\u20131981\n|-\n|| [[Arthur Tonge]] || Labor || [[Electoral district of Canterbury|Canterbury]] || 1926\u20131932, 1935\u20131962\n|-\n|| Hon [[Vernon Treatt]] || Liberal || [[Electoral district of Woollahra|Woollahra]] || 1938\u20131962\n|-\n|| [[Laurie Tully]] || Labor || [[Electoral district of Goulburn|Goulburn]] || 1946\u20131965\n|-\n|| [[William Wattison]] || Labor || [[Electoral district of Sturt (New South Wales)|Sturt]] || 1947\u20131968\n|-\n|| [[Bill Weiley]] || Labor || [[Electoral district of Clarence|Clarence]] || 1955\u20131971\n|-\n|| [[Ernest Wetherell]] || Labor || [[Electoral district of Cobar|Cobar]] || 1949\u20131965\n|-\n|| [[Eric Willis]] || Labor || [[Electoral district of Earlwood|Earlwood]] || 1950\u20131978\n|-\n|| [[Stan Wyatt]] || Labor || [[Electoral district of Lakemba|Lakemba]] || 1950\u20131964\n|-\n|}\n\n:{{note label|1|1|1}} The 1959 re-election of Lismore Country Party MLA [[Jack Easter]] was overturned by the Court of Disputed Returns on 12 June 1959. Labor candidate [[Keith Compton]] won the [[1959 Lismore state by-election|resulting by-election]] on 12 September.\n:{{note label|2|2|2}} Oxley MLA [[Les Jordan]] had been re-elected as a Country Party member in 1959, but defected to the Liberal Party late that year.\n:{{note label|3|3|3}} Cook\u2019s River Labor MLA and Premier [[Joseph Cahill]] died on 22 October 1959. His son, Labor candidate [[Tom Cahill (Australian politician)|Tom Cahill]], won the [[1959 Cook\u2019s River state by-election|resulting by-election]] on 12 December.\n:{{note label|4|4|4}} Kurri Kurri Labor MLA [[George Booth (Australian politician)|George Booth]] died on 31 July 1960. His son, Labor candidate [[Ken Booth (politician)|Ken Booth]], won the [[1960 Kurri Kurri state by-election|resulting by-election]] on 8 October.\n:{{note label|5|5|5}} Temora Country Party MLA [[Doug Dickson]] died on 27 July 1960. Country Party candidate [[Jim Taylor (politician)|Jim Taylor]] won the [[1960 Temora state by-election|resulting by-election]] on 8 October.\n:{{note label|6|6|6}} Paddington-Waverley Labor MLA [[William Ferguson (1891-1961)|William Ferguson]] died on 29 January 1961. Labor candidate [[Keith Anderson (Australian politician)|Keith Anderson]] won the [[1961 Paddington-Waverley state by-election|resulting by-election]] on 25 February.\n:{{note label|7|7|7}} Liverpool Plains Labor MLA [[Roger Nott]] resigned on 3 March 1961 to accept an appointment as [[Administrator of the Northern Territory]]. Country Party candidate [[Frank O'Keefe]] won the [[1961 Liverpool Plains state by-election|resulting by-election]] on 25 March.\n:{{note label|8|8|8}} Blacktown MLA [[Alfred Dennis]] was elected as a representative of the Liberal Party, but resigned to sit as an independent in 1962 after losing a preselection challenge for the safer Liberal seat of [[electoral district of The Hills|The Hills]].\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[1959 New South Wales state election]]\n* Premiers: \n** [[Joseph Cahill]] ([[Australian Labor Party (New South Wales Branch)|Labor]]) (1952\u20131959)\n** [[Robert Heffron]] ([[Australian Labor Party (New South Wales Branch)|Labor]]) (1959\u20131964)\n\n{{Members of the Parliament of New South Wales}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Members of the New South Wales Legislative Assembly, 1959-1962}}\n[[Category:Members of New South Wales parliaments by term]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=November 2016}}\nThis is a list of '''members of the [[New South Wales Legislative Assembly]]''' from 1959 to 1962, as elected at the [[1959 New South Wales state election|1959 state election]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#cccccc\"\n! '''Name'''\n! '''Party'''\n! '''[[New South Wales Legislative Assembly electoral districts|Electorate]]'''\n! '''Term in office'''\n|-\n|| [[Keith Anderson (Australian politician)|Keith Anderson]] {{ref label|6|6|6}} || [[Australian Labor Party (New South Wales Branch)|Labor]] || [[Electoral district of Paddington-Waverley|Paddington-Waverley]] || 1961-1962\n|-\n|| Hon [[Robert Askin]] || [[Liberal Party of Austral